(447, 4, 'guard_ab5da53725f49764c65a261e720e099f', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2011/oct/16/arsenal-sunderland-live', 'Arsenal v Sunderland | Gregg Roughley', 'Gregg Roughley', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Football/Clubs/Club_Home/2011/10/16/1318763343754/Tony-Adams-003.jpg', '2011-10-16 16:25:00', NULL, '<p><strong>Minute-by-minute report:</strong> Robin van Persie was in inspired form, as his two goals gave a nervy Arsenal a much-needed three points at the Emirates</p>', '<!-- Block 1 --><h2>Preamble</h2><!-- Block 2 --><p>Considering his team have conceded 16 goals in seven matches, Arsène Wenger seems surprisingly optimistic about his defence. Tony Adams can be the new "Per Mertesacker", oh hang on, Per Mertesacker can be the "new Tony Adams". Or something like that. And with Laurent Koscielny and Johan Djourou on their way back to full fitness, Wenger believes his defence can plug the leaks. Now considering those two were at the heart of the defence on that shambolic day at Old Trafford, he may need to give his rose-tinted glasses a little wipe and reassess things. Thomas Vermaelen would make a difference if he came back, mind, but he''s still a couple of weeks away, and given the amount of time he''s been out he may take a while to regain the kind of form he showed when he was signed a couple of years ago. Wenger''s biggest challenge will be how to shore up the right full-back spot since Bacary Sagna broke his leg. Carl Jenkinson, despite his promise, hardly had any experience in League One with Charlton, so to ask him to replace Sagna, who has been a fixture in the Arsenal side for years now, is a big ask.</p><p>Mind you, things aren''t all that rosy at Sunderland. At boardroom level the club is unstable, Steve Bruce is under intense pressure after spending big and delivering little, and fans are understandably miffed. </p><p>The good omen for the Mackems, though, is that the last time they won away at Arsenal (in 1983) the Brinks Mat Robbery took place. There''s been another huge theft this year that''s been big in this newsroom. My colleague Jacob Steinberg''s iPod was stolen … IN GUARDIAN TOWERS! Yes, you may think these offices are a utopian haven free from the evil of the world, but nobody''s safe. I''m clinging on to my mouse for all it''s worth (£10) in case some light-fingered villain gets to work when I nod off in the first half.</p><p><strong>My prediction: </strong> Arsenal 2-1 Sunderland</p><!-- Block 3 --><h2>The teams</h2><p><strong>Arsenal: </strong>Szczesny, Jenkinson, Koscielny, Mertesacker, Gibbs, Song, Arteta, Rosicky, Walcott, van Persie, Gervinho. <strong>Subs:</strong> Fabianski, Park, Andre Santos, Djourou, Arshavin, Frimpong, Benayoun.<br /><strong>Sunderland: </strong> Mignolet, O''Shea, Turner, Brown, Richardson, Elmohamady, Vaughan, Colback, Cattermole, Larsson, Sessegnon.<br /><strong>Subs:</strong> Westwood, Gardner, Wickham, Ji, Meyler, McClean, Laing.<br /><strong>Referee:</strong> Howard Webb (S Yorkshire)</p><!-- Block 4 --><p><span class="timestamp">1.23pm:</span> "Hey Gregg, sad to hear on Football Weekly that you haven''t yet being able to adopt your wife''s cool NY Jewish intellectual Beat Poet style surname [Bakowski], but, if you''re looking to make the most of it, why not start doing a weekly Guardian blog/pod about Liverpool called "Roughly Speaking"? It would work on like multiple levels!" whoops Ryan Dunne. Sorry to whazz on your parade, Ryan, but I imagine it would fail when the comments section degenerates into a competition to see who can create the best Roughley-related pun.</p><!-- Block 5 --><p><span class="timestamp">1.27pm:</span> Well, it''s almost time to kick-off. Especially for Lee Cattermole. I expect he will try to break up play in midfield whenever he can. My prediction is a booking for Cattermole inside 25 minutes. He can''t help himself. Arteta''s probably wearing two pairs of socks around his ankles.</p><!-- Block 6 --><p><span class="timestamp">Goal! Arsenal 1-0 Sunderland (Van Persie 1min):</span>  What a start! With 27 seconds on the clock, Rosicky clips a ball down the inside-left channel to Gervinho. He races 20 yards forwards under no pressure, turns inside and plays a simple square ball to Van Persie, 20 yards from goal. With Wes Brown standing off him, Van Persie takes one touch and picks his spot in the bottom right-hand corner of Sunderland''s goal perfectly.</p><!-- Block 7 --><p><span class="timestamp">3 min:</span> Steve Bruce will have felt the air get a little heavier around his shoulders as that ball went in. Sunderland''s defence were lethargic, to say the least. O''Shea didn''t get half as close to Gervinho as he should have been and, despite Van Persie''s clever step back away from Brown, some effort could have been made to block his shot.</p><!-- Block 8 --><p><span class="timestamp">7 min:</span> Arsenal have settled into this like they''re wearing slippers. It''s a pity so many Arsenal fans haven''t turned up at the Emirates to watch them. They might have seen a decent match, given the home side''s showing so far. Gervinho shifts his weight right and left and knocks the ball to the byline before crossing low to Van Persie, but Brown clears for a corner.</p><!-- Block 9 --><p><span class="timestamp">9 min:</span> Corner comes to nowt, mind. Sunderland have their first attack after a long punt upfield by Mignolet. They win a corner on the left, but it''s about as effective as Arsenal''s.</p><!-- Block 10 --><p><span class="timestamp">11 min:</span> Van Persie produces a wonderful piece of skill. Arteta plays a simple ball to him on the right corner of the penalty area, where the Dutch striker spins Richardson with such speed and grace that the defender''s left looking like he''s been ditched on the dancefloor. Van Persie then does a Cantona and chips Minolet from 18 yards, but as the ball sails towards the left hand corner it clips the post and bounces across the goal-line to be cleared. Deserved a goal. It was lovely.</p><!-- Block 11 --><p><span class="timestamp">14 min:</span> Now if Jamie Redknapp was to describe how Van Persie was playing at the moment it would be H .. L....... O. F...  You can fill in the blanks. He''s playing brilliantly though. He strikes narrowly wide from the edge of the box after another incisive move in midfield. Sunderland can''t string a pass together. They''ve not turned up.</p><!-- Block 12 --><p><span class="timestamp">17 min:</span> Here''s our European scout Rob Moline. "Best right-back going round at the moment is Mauricio Isla at Udinese - everyone was raving about Alexis Sanchez last year getting Udinese into Big Cup, but every time you watched them you saw Isla flashing past him forwards in attack and backwards in defence - he is fit! (in the aerobic capacity sense). Starred for Chile in the World Cup, too, again alongside Sanchez. I kinda hope he ends up at Barça replacing Dani Alves, Arsenal has jumped the shark but Barça are still pretty good*. Barça missed a trick not signing the two of them in summer." Van Persie almost causes Wes Brown to break his ankle as he flicks the ball from right to left at lightspeed and then tries to slip Gervinho in through a gap in Sunderland''s defence. O''Shea gets a foot to it and Van Persie tries to hook a second pass back into the danger area, but Mignolet gathers comfortably.</p><!-- Block 13 --><p><span class="timestamp">20 min:</span> Larsson bundles Arteta over in midfield. Where''s Cattermole? I haven''t seen him touch the ball or kick anyone yet. Gervinho is causing Sunderland all kinds of problems on the left. O''Shea is caught out for pace again, with Brown having to cover for his former Manchester United team-mate and deflect Gervinho''s cross out for a corner. The corner is swung deep by Arteta to the backpost where Sunderland don''t deal with it and Mignolet collects at the second attempt.</p><!-- Block 14 --><p><span class="timestamp">24 min:</span> Arsenal build another attack from the back with such ease. Song, Rosicky and Arteta are shifting the ball so quickly that Sunderland''s midfield three can''t get close to them. Gervinho is involved in another Arsenal attack, cutting inside his marker just outside the box and slamming a shot against Brown. That Tony Adams is doing well at the back too.</p><!-- Block 15 --><p><span class="timestamp">27 min:</span> Oh, hang on. This wouldn''t have happened if Adams was captain. Koscielny doesn''t listen to Mertesacker as he pushes forwards to play Sessegnon offside and the Sunderland winger is sent scuttling clear on the left. Szczesny rushes out 10 yards outside his area on the left but misses the tackle. Sessegnon turns inside and looks for Vaughan rushing into the box, but Song clears after tracking back diligently. That was very ''new Arsenal''.</p><!-- Block 16 --><p><span class="timestamp">Goal! Arsenal 1-1 Sunderland (Larsson 31 min):</span> A wonderful free-kick from Seb Larsson. Arteta did a Cattermole on Cattermole and smacked him with an errant elbow when jumping for a ball on the edge of the Arsenal box. A free-kick is given and up steps the former Arsenal player. The ball is dead centre 25 yards out. He runs left to right at it and whips it viciously over the wall and into the top left-hand corner at terrific speed. Szczesny had no chance.</p><!-- Block 17 --><p><span class="timestamp">32 min:</span> Well that was a turn up for the books. Arsenal have been completely dominant. Sunderland haven''t done a tap all game. Suddenly Steve Bruce''s side have a head of steam.</p><!-- Block 18 --><p><span class="timestamp">34 min:</span> Sunderland work the ball out to Sessegnon on the left, who has again got clear of Jenkinson. The forward looks more surprised than anything else as he wanders into the Arsenal box unchallenged. He does well to hold the ball up and then clip a wonderful ball past Mertesacker to Cattermole, who races in at the backpost and fires a header from two yards at goal, to be denied by a wonderful block from Szczesny, who flings himself in front of it.</p><!-- Block 19 --><p><span class="timestamp">38 min:</span> This has suddenly become one of those games for Arsenal.</p><!-- Block 20 --><p><span class="timestamp">39 min:</span> Cattermole locates his studs and uses them to good effect to give away a needless free-kick 35 yards from goal. I didn''t see whose ankles felt their steeliness, but there''s no lasting damage and no yellow card for Cattermole either.</p><!-- Block 21 --><p><span class="timestamp">41 min:</span> Rosicky pirouettes away from Cattermole in midfield. Drawing the tackle and then giving himself space. He works the ball to Song, who launches an attack on the right, which finally results in a corner on the left. Despite the towering presence of Mertesacker and Song in the box, there''s no great threat as the ball is flicked up into the air by the big German and eventually headed softly at goal by Song.</p><!-- Block 22 --><p><span class="timestamp">43 min:</span> It''s gone a bit flat. Nothing to see here. "Hi Gregg, nice to see from Wenger''s quotes that it''s not just the English that resort to lazy nationalistic clichés - "Trust the Germans, they can fight." What''s the French for "they don''t like it up ''em"? To answer Patrick Cullen''s question it''s Ils ne l''aiment pas à eux.</p><!-- Block 23 --><p><span class="timestamp">45 min:</span> Larsson is left unmarked at the backpost. He heads the ball back across goal where Colback pokes a toe out and sends the ball just a yard over. That would have been a real kick in the teeth for Arsenal. Though after conceding those familiar jitters have seeped into their play like a nasty virus.</p><!-- Block 24 --><p><span class="timestamp">Half-time</span><br />Is Rosicky like that kid in the Sixth Sense? "I noticed that Rosicky didn''t even turn to see the ball go in the net from the free-kick but had a knowing look on his face. Same thing happened in the Man U Arsenal game when Rooney scored," begins Craig Kilgour. "Does Rosicky know the flight so well he can feel it''s already a goal or does he just not bother following up? I know he got stick on MOTD in the Man U game for it."</p><!-- Block 25 --><p>Looking back at the first-half highlights it''s extraordinary that Arsenal have gone in level. There was only one team playing football until Larsson''s free-kick. Since then, Sunderland have started to pass the ball, win tackles, chase lost causes and they''ve looked, well, like they give a toss. Which they didn''t for the first half an hour. </p><p><strong>I saw a good film last night:</strong> Midnight in Paris by Woody Allen. Go see it. If you like Wes Anderson films it''ll be up your street.</p><!-- Block 26 --><p><span class="timestamp">45 min:</span> The teams are back out at a sparse looking Emirates Stadium. Arsenal are kicking from right to left on my little screen, with Sunderland in light blue pointing the other way, so draw a picture of that in your minds.</p><!-- Block 27 --><p><span class="timestamp">46 min:</span> Gervinho miscontrols in the middle of a promising attack and the ball squirts loose to Cattermole. He looks to set Sessegnon clear down the right-hand channel but Koscielny tracks back and Arsenal win back possession.</p><!-- Block 28 --><p><span class="timestamp">48 min:</span> Apparently Steve Bruce went to Asia in the international break to try and promote Sunderland. As if he hasn''t suffered enough this season. I imagine lots of blank faces greeted him, poor sod. Arsenal are dominating possession again as they did in the first 30 minutes of the first half.</p><!-- Block 29 --><p><span class="timestamp">50 min:</span> Walcott picks the ball up on the right and works his way into the Sunderland penalty area. He plays a low cross across the six-yard box, which Mignolet tries to grab, but pushes out into the crowded penalty area where a collection of legs make a hash of clearing it, resulting in a corner ... which comes to nowt.</p><!-- Block 30 --><p><span class="timestamp">51 min:</span> Kieran Gibbs off, Andre Santos on. The young left back must have picked up a knock.</p><!-- Block 31 --><p><span class="timestamp">52 min:</span> Rosicky races through the middle of midfield and gets hauled down by a cynical challenge by Vaughan, who is rightly booked. Arsenal make a right pig''s ear of a short-free kick, though, which Van Persie ends up skying. It was the antithesis of the class he showed in the first half.</p><!-- Block 32 --><p><span class="timestamp">55 min:</span> Sunderland have collectively sharpened their studs. Larsson is booked for clattering into Van Persie midway inside Sunderland''s half.</p><!-- Block 33 --><p><span class="timestamp">56 min:</span> Rosicky plays a glorious ball all of 40 yards from left to right, landing the leather on Walcott''s toe. He plays a game of who-can-run-fastest with Kieran Richardson down the right wing (it''s a dead heat) with his cross hitting the full-back''s arm inside the area, and Arsenal fans shouting for a penalty, which it would have been harsh to award, as his arms were pretty much against his body.</p><!-- Block 34 --><p><span class="timestamp">59 min:</span> Arsenal win a free-kick in the exacts same spot 25 yards from goal where Larsson scored his pearler from in the first half. But the Spaniard curls an ugly effort over by at least 10 yards. Poor.</p><!-- Block 35 --><p><span class="timestamp">60 min:</span> Sunderland are racking the free-kicks up. If there was an orange card for an offence somewhere between yellow and red, Wes Brown would be a candidate after his cynical tackle on Theo Walcott right on the edge of the box on the left-hand side. The defender slides into Walcott with no hope of winning the ball as he races through. Walcott fancies his chances after seeing Arteta''s dreadful attempt, but his curled effiort is almost as bad, flying way over the bar in an attempt at finding the top right-hand corner.</p><!-- Block 36 --><p><span class="timestamp">64 min:</span> "I''m a little late to this party, but I noticed Ryan Dunne''s comment about "Bakowski," your soon-to-be "cool NY Jewish intellectual Beat Poet style" name. Not to be pedantic, but is he thinking of Charles Bukowski, who emerged as a literary icon from the streets of South Central Los Angeles? Not that you care about my opinion, but if I were you, I''d stay Roughley but maybe change your first name to Greg to simplify things. And you''re right, Midnight in Paris was really good. I''m intrigued by all of these post-New York Woody Allen movies. I think Cassandra''s Dream was underrated, what do you think?" I haven''t seen it but if I did I''d probably think that his 2007 <em>excursion to the dark side of human nature, is good enough that you may wonder why he doesn''t just stop making comedies once and for all</em>. Not that I''ve copied and pasted an opinion on it from another website or anything. Van Persie sidefoots an effort straight at Mignolet from a narrowing angle 10 yards out on the left.</p><!-- Block 37 --><p><span class="timestamp">67 min:</span> Dong-Won Ji replaces Sunderland''s free-kick scoring Seb Larsson. And Andrey Arshavin replaces Gervinho. I''m surprised by that. He''s caused Sunderland''s defence an awful lot of problems with his pace and all round jinkery.</p><!-- Block 38 --><p><span class="timestamp">68 min:</span> Michael Turner stops Arshavin in his tracks with a joyful block tackle. It really was joyful. Stopped Arshavin dead with a lovely thumping sound.</p><!-- Block 39 --><p><span class="timestamp">71 min:</span> Sunderland are looking a bit more comfortable now. They''re reading Arsenal''s passes better and the tension around the Emirates is palpable. Song nutmegs Cattermole beautifully and strides onto his handy bit of work before ruining it all with an overhit pass towards Walcott, who was darting into the box on the right side. Groan!</p><!-- Block 40 --><p><span class="timestamp">73 min:</span> There was a flash of retro-Arshavin about the little Russian''s attack just then. He burst into the box and slalomed through O''Shea, Brown and Turner before poking a shot a yard wide from 15 yards. Would have been a lovely goal, for sure, with a dash of 2008 about it.</p><!-- Block 41 --><p><span class="timestamp">76 min:</span> Rosicky off and Yossi Benayoun on for Arsenal. Meanwhile, here''s my impact sub Gary Naylor: "Just as the best organised teams find a way to win, those not organised well find a way to avoid winning. No surprise to me that Arsenal have gone in level. Wenger''s management is like Paul McCartney''s career. Blazing start then a long descent into vague ill-focused stuff ameliorated by a very occasional highlight. And living off past greatest hits." Ameliorated? Quick look up in the dictionary. Yup, that makes sense.</p><!-- Block 42 --><p><span class="timestamp">78 min:</span> Arsenal are pushing on with a bit more urgency now. Arshavin has had an immediate impact. He curls a dangerous cross towards Van Persie on the back post, but Wes Brown leaps highest and heads the ball out for a corner.</p><!-- Block 43 --><p><span class="timestamp">79 minutes:</span> Sessegnon off and Conor Wickham on for Sunderland. A big man up top. Just the man to give Arsenal the jitters again if Sunderland were to get a corner with minutes to go.</p><!-- Block 44 --><p><span class="timestamp">80 min:</span> "Song picks up possession and looks towards a packed midfield for a pass. He finds Benayoun, who shifts the ball quickly to Van Persie, he spins too quickly for Brown and wins a free-kick in the kind of territory he will love to have a go from.</p><!-- Block 45 --><p><span class="timestamp">Goal! Arsenal 2-1 Sunderland (82 min):</span> Another fantastic free-kick! That''s perfectly placed into the top corner and richly deserved. The Dutchman took one look up and curled it deliciously over the wall (which can''t be blamed) and into the postage stamp at the top right-hand corner of Sunderland''s goal. Van Persie has been purring all day.</p><!-- Block 46 --><p><span class="timestamp">84 min:</span> Dong Won-ji has a goal disallowed after turning in the Arsenal box. He was half a yard offside, but for a moment the crowd didn''t know it. Arsenal need to show a bit of backbone now and unlearn that ability they have of finding a way to cock things up.</p><!-- Block 47 --><p><span class="timestamp">87 min:</span> Craig Gardner is on for Lee Cattermole. Sunderland appeal for a penalty after Theo Walcott at once gets a toe to the ball and Colback''s foot. The Sunderland player goes down but is quickly told to get on his feet again by Howard Webb.</p><!-- Block 48 --><p><span class="timestamp">88 min:</span> "Since this match is probably as exciting on TV as it is on MBM, maybe your readers would like to hear my Superstar Donkey story," writes Alix Sharkey JUST AS THE MATCH IS GETTING EXCITING! "In 1994 I was in a London nightclub called The End, standing at a bar eight deep waiting to get two beers. Having claimed them I turned and to my amazement, recognized the bloke waiting patiently behind me. ''Tony Adams!'' I exclaimed. He smiled broadly but glanced from side to side in a ''don''t break my cover'' kind of way. As we shook hands I said, ''I''m a Spurs fan,'' just to watch his smile turn into a grimace. But he was very magnanimous, and we chatted for a few minutes. About an hour later I found him leaning against a pillar and remarked on his enormous feet, swatched in brown brogues. ''They''re size 12s,'' he conceded. ''But useful on the pitch.'' At that point a very sexy woman in a green minidress walked between us, caught her toe on Adams'' oversize plates, and went sprawling face-first. He looked at me with a wry smile. ''Told you,'' he said."</p><!-- Block 49 --><p><span class="timestamp">90 min:</span> Theo Walcott cuts inside Richardson and accelerates into the box. He looks up but does a very Walcott thing and picks the wrong option. Well, gives it straight to a Sunderland defender to be exact.</p><!-- Block 50 --><p><span class="timestamp">90+1 min:</span> There''s five minutes of injury time. Wenger''s having a good old moan about that. Arsenal are tidy in possession though and, dare I say it, composed at the moment. That Tony Adams story has got me thinking about a similar experience I had in Liverpool with Erik Meijer. Not quite in Adams''s star category, admittedly. But a cult hero in his own clumsy way.</p><!-- Block 51 --><p><span class="timestamp">90+3min:</span> Sunderland get hold of possession at last. Wickham tries a shot from long range which Mertesacker blocks. Benayoun breaks and Arsenal try to work the ball to Van Persie, but Sunderland clear and then win a free-kick.</p><!-- Block 52 --><p><span class="timestamp">90+5min:</span> Mignolet lofts the free-kick high into Arsenal''s penalty area where the whole of Sunderland''s outfield players are gathered. The ball is overhit though and goes out for a goal-kick, much to the relief of the Arsenal fans. Peep! It''s all over.</p><!-- Block 53 --><h2>Full-time</h2><p>Well Arsenal get the three points, which they deserve given their dominance for 75 minutes of the match. Robin van Persie showed why he is now Arsenal''s most important player. At times he was unplayable, but his good work can often be undone by the lack of confidence that leaks into the team when they concede a goal. And what a goal. There was no blame to be attached to any Arsenal player, it was just an amazing free-kick by Larsson. Steve Bruce can be satisfied that his team found their fight at last after the goal and only another piece of brilliance by Van Persie prevented them from getting a point. He''s still under shed loads off pressure, mind. I''ll leave the final word to Neil Brown: "I saw ''Midnight In Paris'' a few days ago and really enjoyed it; really witty and charming. The fella who played Hemmingway was as good as Adrien Brody''s Dali was bad. The theme of the film is particularly prescient for fans of Arsenal (my team) and Liverpool (your team, I believe); namely that nostalgia only gets a person so far and one needs to embrace, and make the most of, the present. I also saw ''Drive'', which was incredibly exciting, well put together yet look-away-now violent, and all the better for it. Is that one for Stoke fans?"</p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/football&k=Premier+League+2011-12&k=Arsenal&k=Sunderland&k=Premier+League&k=Sport&k=Football" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/football/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/football/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=Arsenal+v+Sunderland+%7C+Gregg+Roughley+Article+1648328&ch=Football&c2=60753&c4=Premier+League+2011-12%2CArsenal+FC+%28Football%29%2CSunderland+%28Football%29%2CPremier+League+%28Football%29%2CSport%2CFootball&c3=guardian.co.uk&c6=Gregg+Roughley&c7=11-Oct-16&c8=1648328&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: football/2011/oct/16/arsenal-sunderland-live|2011-10-16T21:13:21+01:00|39f6364e8bc8cebeb9a8441c32d701fe913d2860 -->', NULL, 'Football', 'guardian.co.uk', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:25'),
