(449, 4, 'guard_dcb1b1510e10e5cd5fe10c6e14f1c109', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2011/oct/16/dragons-den-gallagher-presidential-poll', 'Dragons'' Den star emerges as main man in Ireland''s presidential race', 'Henry McDonald, Ireland correspondent', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Users/Help/screenshots/2011/10/16/1318774094132/Martin-McGuiness-003.jpg', '2011-10-16 16:38:35', NULL, 'Independent candidate Sean Gallagher tops Sunday newspaper poll with 39% support', '<p>One of the stars of Ireland''s version of Dragons'' Den is in the lead in the race to become the republic''s next president.</p><p>Independent candidate Sean Gallagher has 39% support according to a Red C poll for the Sunday Business Post newspaper.</p><p>Gallagher was on the panel of millionaires in the RTÉ version of Dragons'' Den, a reality TV programme in which entrepreneurs pitch business ideas to a panel of venture capitalists.</p><p>The poll says he has jumped 18 points in nine days and that the Irish Labour candidate and former arts minister Michael D Higgins is in second place with 27%.</p><p>But support for Sinn Féin''s Martin McGuinness has fallen to 13%. The former IRA chief of staff has faced repeated questions over his role as a leading figure in the Provisionals during the Troubles.</p><p>The poll was taken before a row broke out at the end of last week between Sinn Féin and RTÉ, the national broadcaster. McGuinness was outraged over a question during a live presidential debate on Wednesday night when he was asked how he squared his Catholic beliefs with support for IRA murders.</p><p>The Sinn Féin deputy first minister of Northern Ireland demanded a private meeting with the programme''s presenter, Miriam O''Callaghan, to complain about the line of questioning during the debate.</p><p>The Red C polls suggests that gay rights campaigner David Norris is out of the running with only 7% support, while Gay Mitchell, the candidate for the largest party in the Republic, Fine Gael, has only 8%.</p><p>The poll was taken on Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday, before the RTÉ Prime Time debate was held.</p><p>Last week, McGuinness was verbally attacked by two relatives of Irish security force members the IRA killed in the 1980s.</p><p>The son of Irish army soldier Patrick Kelly ambushed McGuinness during a canvass of Athlone town and challenged him to name those in the IRA he knew were responsible for shooting his father dead during a kidnap rescue attempt.</p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/world&k=Ireland&k=World+news&k=Sinn+F%C3%A9in&k=Martin+McGuinness&k=Politics&k=IRA" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/world/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/world/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=Dragons%27+Den+star+emerges+as+main+man+in+Ireland%27s+presidential+race+Article+1648356&ch=World+news&c2=60753&c4=Ireland+%28News%29%2CWorld+news%2CSinn+Fein%2CMartin+McGuinness%2CPolitics%2CIRA+%28formerly+Provisional.+NOT+Real+or+Continuity+or+Official%29%2CUK+news%2CDragons+Den%2CTelevision+and+radio+TV&c3=The+Guardian&c6=Henry+McDonald%2C+Ireland+correspondent&c7=11-Oct-16&c8=1648356&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: world/2011/oct/16/dragons-den-gallagher-presidential-poll|2011-10-16T21:13:21+01:00|e2babb4ad4fcea1a07f615a2105e264d42e4b110 -->', NULL, 'World news', 'The Guardian', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:25'),
