(454, 4, 'guard_e588f71937e0fd1197ad887c1e8ea222', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2011/oct/16/luis-suarez-patrice-evra-racism', 'Luis Suárez upset by allegations he racially abused Patrice Evra', 'Agencies', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Football/Clubs/Club_Home/2011/10/16/1318777849656/Luis-Su-rez-and-Patrice-E-003.jpg', '2011-10-16 17:12:00', NULL, 'Luis Suárez said he was upset by accusations that he racially abused Patrice Evra during the 1-1 draw at Anfield', '<!-- Redistribution rights for this field are unavailable -->', NULL, 'Football', 'guardian.co.uk', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:25'),
(455, 4, 'guard_1b7460f160edcd14107198066dde52ee', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2011/oct/16/eu-plans-50bn-infrastructure-jobs-campaign', 'EU to reveal €50bn infrastructure jobs plan', 'David Gow in Brussels', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/cartoons/2011/10/16/1318778524224/EU-commissioner-for-Digit-003.jpg', '2011-10-16 17:23:21', NULL, 'EU hopes €50bn investment in digital, energy and transport infrastructure will attract more private finance, creating hundreds of thousands of jobs', '<p>The EU will this week launch plans to invest €50bn (£44bn) in modernising digital, energy and transport networks, creating hundreds of thousands of jobs over the next few years.</p><p>The European commission scheme envisages the use of bonds backed by the European Investment Bank (EIB) to fill funding gaps left by cash-strapped governments and leverage up private investment.</p><p>The plans, due to be revealed on Wednesday, are designed to pay back taxpayers for the aid and guarantees of €4.6tn given to the financial sector in the past three years. Despite this taxpayer funded support, venture capital investments in Europe slumped last year to just €3bn.</p><p>EIB president Philippe Maystadt said: "Infrastructure finance in Europe has suffered since the financial crisis and banks face new constraints on long term lending. Project bonds could be a way to attract capital from other investors, such as pension funds and insurance companies, and be a useful addition to traditional financing options."</p><p>The EC says developing smart infrastructure could require up to €1.5-2tn for trans-European transport networks, the energy sector and information and communication technologies. That equates to the putative size of the eurozone bailout fund discussed by G20 finance ministers at the weekend.</p><p>The bulk of the funds to be announced this week (around €32bn) would go to transport infrastructure projects, with €9bn each earmarked for energy, including smart grids, and for broadband infrastructure and digital public services.</p><p>High-speed broadband would receive €7bn between 2014 and 2020 — enough, according to Neelie Kroes, digital agenda commissioner, to leverage more than €50bn of public and private investment by lowering the risk attached to projects.</p><p>Kroes said the money would be largely in the form of equity, debt or guarantees provided by the EU and EIB, thus improving the credit rating of projects. These would be proposed not only by telecoms operators but water and electricity utilities, co-ops or construction firms.</p><p>The aim, her officials said, is to support investment in less obviously attractive broadband infrastructure projects such as those in remote rural areas.</p><p>The EU estimates that €270bn needs to be invested to meet its 2020 target of broadband at 30 megabits a second for all Europeans and 100Mbps for half of them.</p><p>The EC estimates that the roll-out of high-speed broadband networks in Germany alone would create 1m jobs between now and 2020 while French plans for a fibre-to-the-home network could generate 360,000 jobs a year.</p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/business&k=European+debt+crisis&k=European+banks&k=Business&k=European+Union&k=World+news&k=Neelie+Kroes" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/business/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/business/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=EU+to+reveal+%E2%82%AC50bn+infrastructure+jobs+plan+Article+1648380&ch=Business&c2=60753&c4=European+debt+crisis%2CEuropean+banks+%28business%29%2CBusiness%2CEuropean+Union+%28News%29%2CWorld+news%2CNeelie+Kroes%2CEurope+%28Business%29%2CBroadband%2CInternet%2CTechnology&c3=The+Guardian&c6=David+Gow+in+Brussels&c7=11-Oct-16&c8=1648380&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: business/2011/oct/16/eu-plans-50bn-infrastructure-jobs-campaign|2011-10-16T21:13:24+01:00|5962732a48d0938d26501592713aed40d09ca57a -->', NULL, 'Business', 'The Guardian', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:27'),
(456, 4, 'guard_ffd4ff68bdd7a7aecae4ca8df3a463d8', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/blog/2011/oct/16/southern-italy-organised-crime-euro-boom', 'Europe on the breadline: why southern Italy missed out on the ''euro boom''', 'Jon Henley', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Admin/BkFill/Default_image_group/2011/10/16/1318769641239/barletta-explosion-003.jpg', '2011-10-16 17:30:00', NULL, '<p>Jon Henley hears from someone in Milan who wonders if southern Italians are more psychologically prepared for crisis  </p>', '<p>Gemma Thomas from Milan writes with a horrendous tale of an explosion earlier this month at a clothing sweatshop in Barletta, Puglia, southern Italy: "Working 12 hours a day at €4 an hour, from their hospital beds the survivors'' main concern was getting back to their jobs so that they could pay the mortgage."</p><p>Gemma says: "The strength of organised crime in the south [of Italy] has meant that the ''normal'' people living in the regions you are visiting have never really experienced the ''euro boom'' experienced in Greece, Spain and Portugal. For decades, the majority of the money given by the EU or state for improving infrastructure has disappeared, leaving people without jobs and totally dependant on the state for help.</p><p>"If anything, Italians have got progressively poorer since the introduction of the euro in 2002: the cost of products and services doubled overnight while salaries (and pensions) did not!</p><p>"But in my opinion, southern Italians could be more psychologically prepared for the crisis than anybody else. It is here in the industrial heartland of Italy (from Turin to Bologna) where the crisis is really being felt. The medium-size Italian factories that characterised the Italian boom of the 1970s and 1980s are being forced to close and neither the Italian newspapers nor the Italian politicians want to speak about it."</p><p>• If you have a story to tell, know a person I should talk to or live in a place you think I should visit, please contact me: jon.henley@guardian.co.uk, or @jonhenley (the hashtag for this venture is #EuroDebtTales)</p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/world&k=Italy&k=European+debt+crisis&k=Europe&k=World+news" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/world/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/world/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=Europe+on+the+breadline%3A+why+southern+Italy+missed+out+on+the+%27euro+boom%27+Article+1648342&ch=World+news&c2=60753&c4=Italy+%28News%29%2CEuropean+debt+crisis%2CEurope%2CWorld+news&c3=guardian.co.uk&c6=Jon+Henley&c7=11-Oct-16&c8=1648342&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: world/blog/2011/oct/16/southern-italy-organised-crime-euro-boom|2011-10-16T21:13:24+01:00|36f4853da4d1590e7a37c830e17a2ee945931eb7 -->', NULL, 'World news', 'guardian.co.uk', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:27'),
