(473, 4, 'guard_9d68cc0325bd97ad908d4feb0b1da134', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2011/oct/16/newcastle-united-tottenham-hotspur-live', 'Newcastle United v Tottenham Hotspur - as it happened | Jacob Steinberg', 'Jacob Steinberg', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Football/Clubs/Club_Home/2011/9/25/1316968843814/Demba-Ba-celebrates-scori-003.jpg', '2011-10-16 18:57:00', NULL, '<p><strong>Minute-by-minute report:</strong> Shola Ameobi''s late equaliser denied Tottenham victory and maintained Newcastle''s unbeaten start</p>', '<!-- Block 1 --><p><strong>Five or six years ago, there was a clutch of home-grown managers who were tipped for big things.</strong> The Dowies, the Boothroyds, the PBs of this world; sharp-suited or sometimes sharp-tracksuited, they wore Bluetooth headsets, borrowed ideas from the David Brent school of management, operated outside the box and engaged in blue-sky thinking. They all assumed they were the next Arsene Wenger basically, or maybe Steve McClaren, and their names were tentatively floated when big jobs became available. Some were even regarded as future England managers. Anyway, to cut a long story short, they either now manage on the lower leagues, or can now be seen on Gillette Soccer Specials, but usually on midweek Carling Cup nights, never on Saturday afternoons. But there''s one man of that genre who has avoided that grim fate, though there were a few rocky spells, not least when he was sacked by Southampton a year ago. Ladies and gentlemen, without further ado, please give it up for Alan Pardew! </p><p>Initially seen as another part of the Cockney Mafia on Tyneside, Pardew has been carefully rehabilitating his reputation at Newcastle, who are unbeaten and sitting as pretty as bare-chested, pot-bellied Geordies in fourth place. It''s quite a comeback for a side who were relegated to the Championship in 2009 and a manager who was in League One two years ago and unemployed this time last year. Still, a certain amount of caution remains about Newcastle, who are yet to <em>really</em> play anyone of any significance yet. We can discount the draw they got against Arsenal on the first day of the season because, well, just look at them. There have been impressive performances - winning at Sunderland and Wolves for example - but no opposition to truly test them just yet. </p><p>That changes this afternoon. Tottenham have already failed two tests, getting stuffed by the Manchester clubs, and subsequently passed another two, beating Liverpool and Arsenal (and yes, I ruled them out in Newcastle''s case, but north London derbies are different). This promises to be a cracking encounter: Yohan Cabaye v Luka Modric, Scott Parker v Cheik Tiote and Demba Ba v Emmanuel Adebayor. We essentially already know about Tottenham - there''s nothing really left to <em>learn</em> about them - but by 6pm, we could know a lot more about where Newcastle''s season is heading.</p><!-- Block 2 --><p><strong>Do Newcastle''s fans use this chant for Demba Ba?</strong> If not, it''s a dereliction of duty.</p><!-- Block 3 --><p><strong>Here are today''s teams.</strong> Adebayor does start for Spurs, with Jermain Defore replaced by Jake Livermore.</p><p><strong>Newcastle (4-4-2):</strong> Krul; Simpson, Steven Taylor, Coloccini, Ryan Taylor; Obertan, Cabaye, Tiote, Gutierrez; Best, Ba. <strong>Subs:</strong> Elliot, Santon, Ben Arfa, Lovenkrands, Gosling, Marveaux, Shola Ameobi.</p><p><strong>Tottenham (4-4-1-1): </strong>Friedel; Walker, Kaboul, King, Assou-Ekotto;<br />Livermore, Parker, Modric, Bale; Van der Vaart; Adebayor. <strong>Subs:</strong> Cudicini, Pavlyuchenko, Giovani, Defoe, Bassong, Rose, Townsend.</p><p>Referee: Lee Probert (Wiltshire)</p><!-- Block 4 --><p><strong>Oliver Lewis emails.</strong> "Oddly looking forward to this one as a Toon fan, first game where all in all no disaster to drop all 3 points so pressure kinda off and lets have a good game," he says. "Disappointing on teams I hear though, no room for Santon in first team or HBA. Disagree with Pardew''s idea of never changing a winning team, instead should be looking to constantly improve. Santon, Marveaux and Ben Arfa would all make this squad better, when better to give them a proper run out than in a game with less to lose? Would have been nice to start at least once. Come second half though we have strong players coming off the bench."</p><p><strong>Ade Cooper''s also here.</strong> "I''d quite to like to hear Newcastle fans doing a Demba Ba chant to the tune of the Beach Boys'' <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2wbMqRO6lnc">Barbara Ann</a>," he says. I think you meant Barber Ran.</p><!-- Block 5 --><p><strong>Before we get going, enjoy this piece of retro-Premier League action, when Newcastle beat Tottenham 7-1 here back in December 1996.</strong> Kevin Keegan left not long after.</p><!-- Block 6 --><p><strong>Harry Redknapp''s talking, which is never interesting.</strong> "Twenty pints of Guinness please, mate. Every time Demba Ba has scored for West Ham or Newcastle and I''ve heard a commentator blurt out his name, I always think they''re having a momentary flashback to a stag weekend in Dublin," notes Alan Pollock. "Yours on the puke-flecked cobbles of that very same fair city." I don''t think I''ve ever got through a pint of Guinness.</p><!-- Block 7 --><p><strong>The teams are out.</strong> They''ll have to line up next to each other and listen to some music next. Then they can play football.</p><!-- Block 8 --><p><strong>Peep!</strong> And off we go, Newcastle kicking off in the traditional style and attacking from right to left. They''re in their black and white stripes; Tottenham look like Fiorentina, who drew 0-0 with Cesena earlier. Let''s hope that''s not an omen. Interestingly Bale has started on the right for Spurs.</p><!-- Block 9 --><p><strong>2 min:</strong> The early signs are that this is a match that will be played with the very best intentions. Gutierrez threads a glorious eye-of-the-needle pass through to Obertan on the left, but the ball gets stuck under his feet and Walker, who had fallen asleep initially, recovers.</p><!-- Block 10 --><p><strong>3 min:</strong> There are going to be chances in this game. Adebayor dummies Assou-Ekotto''s pass inside from the left, the ball reaching Van der Vaart on the edge of the area. His touch forward is just too heavy though and Ryan Taylor gets across to Peter Kay the ball into the stands.</p><!-- Block 11 --><p><strong>4 min:</strong> "I had no idea this was an international match," toots Ian Copestake. "Is the music they are listening to to mark an official north south divide?" That''s only happening now?</p><!-- Block 12 --><p><strong>5 min:</strong> Parker is penalised for what appeared to be a fair challenge on his old West Ham pal Demba Ba in the middle of Tottenham''s half. Ryan Taylor finds Steven Taylor, who takes the novel step of doing Tottenham''s work for them by generously clearing the ball with a bullet header. If that had been on target, it definitely would have gone in - however he was facing away from goal and managed to direct it towards the centre circle. But still, the technique was great. If you like your headers meaty, you''ll have enjoyed that.</p><!-- Block 13 --><p><strong>8 min:</strong> Kaboul knocks a searching pass forward for Adebayor to take on Steven Taylor, who does brilliantly to stand up to the striker''s strength, hold him off and avert a possible opening for Spurs.</p><!-- Block 14 --><p><strong>9 min:</strong> Van der Vaart and Modric mess up a short-corner routine between them. Do these things ever work? Just get it in the mixer.</p><!-- Block 15 --><p><strong>10 min:</strong> Parker has a prodded pop from 25 yards out. There was no threat to it, but it took a nick on its way through, meaning the jeers from the Newcastle fans are ill-judged. Another corner to Spurs then, but Kaboul''s header from deep inside the area is easily collected by Krul. Tottenham are the better side here, zipping the ball about confidently and attacking with some menace.</p><!-- Block 16 --><p><strong>12 min:</strong> Walker goes in a fraction late on Ryan Taylor on the left, giving the Newcastle left-back another chance to put a cross into the Tottenham area. Taylor swings a dangerous ball into the corridor of uncertainty, as it were, but Friedel keeps his eyes on it and remains unflustered by Obertan''s attempt to get a toe on the cross.</p><!-- Block 17 --><p><strong>15 min:</strong> If Best had been switched on here, he would have been through. Ba tried to slide him in, but King half-cut the pass out. However he didn''t get enough on it, the ball bobbling through anyway, but Best had assumed the chance had gone and was standing in a daydream, much to the chagrin of Newcastle''s fans. "Do short corners work?" asks Joe Mahoney. "Ask Barcelona." They play a different sport.</p><!-- Block 18 --><p><strong>16 min:</strong> Gareth Bale is limping. Maybe he just wants to go back to the left wing.</p><!-- Block 19 --><p><strong>18 min:</strong> Neither keeper has had to make a save yet. Please not one of <em>those</em> games with lots of cleared crosses.</p><!-- Block 20 --><p><strong>19 min:</strong> "What was song Ian Copestake on about?" says Mark Guthrie. "Surely he''s not so London-centric that he has never heard The Balydon Races before? Unless he thinks that Blitzkrieg Bop is the national anthem of the North East? On another matter, While Redknapp is hardly known as a tactical master, putting Bale up against the dodgy at best Ryan Taylor is going to cause problems to Newcastle at only Alan Pardew couldn''t have anticipated. I''m telling you now, that''s where the goals are going to come from." I''m not so sure. Bale is very transparent, it''s obvious he''s only ever going to go inside on to his left foot. If you can squeeze him, he''ll be restricted.</p><!-- Block 21 --><p><strong>21 min:</strong> A lot of ineffectual passing in midfield so far, followed by moves that break down at the very last. "If it''s into the mixer corner you crave then there are sneaky ways of delivering them, as <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pjxuHlK61yM">this set of clips demonstrates</a>," says Ian Copestake. "Better with the sound off unless you like your football clips enhanced by eurotrash anthems."</p><!-- Block 22 --><p><strong>22 min:</strong> Cabaye sprays a great pass out to Obertan on the right to isolate Assou-Ekotto, but the Frenchman''s low centre is put behind by King for a corner.</p><!-- Block 23 --><p><strong>23 min:</strong> The corner is a flagrant waste, Cabaye trying to work a Beckham-Scholes routine with a Newcastle player on the edge of the box. It''s headed away. JUST GET IT IN THE MIXER SON.</p><!-- Block 24 --><p><strong>24 min:</strong> A save for Friedel, if you can call it. Ba rises highest to meet a cross from the left at the far post, but he can''t generate any power on it and it''s straight at Friedel. Hellboy snaffles it with ease.</p><!-- Block 25 --><p><strong>26 min:</strong> I don''t want to seem ungrateful, but this is getting ominously close to dull. Let''s see Ian Ayre try and sell this to Asia.</p><!-- Block 26 --><p><strong>27 min:</strong> "Re Bale I agree wholeheartedly with you, but I think you are possibly overestemating Raylor''s ability to squeeze," says Mark Guthrie. "Oh, and is it just me and Ian Copestake watching the match? Is Gary Naylor on holiday?" Naylor was on the Arsenal-Sunderland mbm, using big words like "ameliorate" apparently.</p><!-- Block 27 --><p><strong>29 min:</strong> Ba and Gutierrez mess up a Newcastle attack. Walker defends well. I''ll just repeat this another 60 times, although the names and teams are interchangeable.</p><!-- Block 28 --><p><strong>30 min:</strong> A desperately sad sight here: Ledley King''s knee (I''m guessing) has flared up and he''s been replaced by Sebastien Bassong, who''s booed on to the pitch. It''s said often, but just how many England caps would King have had if he had working knees? He is brilliant.</p><!-- Block 29 --><p><strong>32 min:</strong> King had placed both Ba and Best snugly in his back-pocket. Bassong and Kaboul suddenly seems a much less secure pairing, with much more potential for farce.</p><!-- Block 30 --><p><strong>33 min:</strong> Apparently Pardew called this a "watershed" game for Newcastle. Now there''s a man who <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Bx94jwmMxPs">knows a thing or two about the watershed</a>.</p><!-- Block 31 --><p><strong>34 min:</strong> As this game is offering us nothing to talk about, let''s turn to events elsewhere. "As a WBA fan may I once again extend thanks to Wolverhampton Wanderers for their gracious yearly gift of three points," says Adam Timmins. "Don''t know what we''d do without them!" You didn''t beat them in either game last season.</p><!-- Block 32 --><p><strong>35 min:</strong> Do you want to hear about a Newcastle corner that was headed away at the near post? Is that really what you want? "I am very angry with you, Jacob," says Ian Copestake. "By mentioning Hellboy my brain is immediately distracted by thoughts of Selma Blair. A period of calm reflection is now required to recover."</p><!-- Block 33 --><p><strong>38 min:</strong> Modric and Van der Vaart have around three touches of the ball between them. Saying that, the former very nearly slipped Adebayor in with a clever reverse-pass, but a sliding Coloccini just cut it out.</p><!-- Block 34 --><p><strong>39 min:</strong> Tottenham have a penalty! And it is as clear as they come, as Steven Taylor bizarrely decides to tackle Adebayor with his ''wrong'' foot in the area and brings him down. Lee Probert takes an age to decide, but after an eternity he points to the spot.</p><!-- Block 35 --><p><strong>GOAL! Newcastle 0-1 Tottenham (Van der Vaart pen, 40 min):</strong> That''s an expertly taken penalty. Van der Vaart wraps his left foot around the ball and whips it into the right corner, Krul going the wrong way and Newcastle''s unbeaten record is under threat now. Newcastle aren''t happy, but it was a clear penalty. Steven Taylor was booked for the foul as Adebayor was going away from goal.</p><!-- Block 36 --><p><strong>42 min:</strong> Newcastle look to hit back immediately but Ba can only send an awkward header well over from Cabaye''s corner. As for the penalty, it was such a stupid challenge from Steven Taylor. His body shape was all wrong, he put his left leg forward when he should have used his right, and as Adebayor nicked the ball ahead of him, it was only ever going to be a clumsy foul.</p><!-- Block 37 --><p><strong>43 min:</strong> Newcastle''s fans are nursing a burning sense of injustice and are booing Adebayor. It was a very uncontroversial decision though.</p><!-- Block 38 --><p><strong>45 min:</strong> "I don''t think King would have won many more caps had he been injury free, because England''s Brave John Terry and Rio Ferdinand stood in his way, the two best defenders in world history according to Sky (and they''re never wrong)," says Jon Allison. "Not unless the midfield was to become even more of a square peg/round hole bodge with King, Lampard and Gerrard in the same team." King''s better than Terry. There, I said it.</p><!-- Block 39 --><p><strong>45 min+1: </strong>"Hawrite Jacob!" says Ryan Dunne. "Am sure that readers of the day''s other MBMs are, like me, itching to know: did you find out who nicked your iPod? Hope it didn''t have lots of embarrassing stuff on it. NB Hellboy is pish, you guys should go read some Cerebus." I don''t know who did. Embarrassing stuff? Will episodes of Football Weekly cover it?</p><!-- Block 40 --><p><strong>Peep! Peep! </strong> Boos greet the half-time whistle from the Newcastle fans, who are booing for the sake of booing. Lee Probert has had an excellent half.</p><!-- Block 41 --><p><strong>Half time: Newcastle 0-1 Tottenham.</strong></p><!-- Block 42 --><p><strong>46 min:</strong> And we''re back. Some early head tennis in the Tottenham area shows us why this is the best league in the world. "Ledley King?" says Harvey Kelly. "Best English defender in living memory if you ask me. And no, I''m not a Tottenham supporter. Imagine if he could train, let alone train with his team-mates, we''d have a Baresi or a Beckenbauer on our hands." Rio Ferdinand is and was better.</p><!-- Block 43 --><p><strong>GOAL! Newcastle 1-1 Tottenham (Ba, 48 min):</strong> This is a brilliant response from Newcastle and they''ve shown us what they''re made of. They''d been far too tentative in attack until now, but suddenly Gutierrez took the game by the scruff of the neck, driving forward from the left. He jinked past a feeble non-challenge from Modric, burst past Walker and hang up a teasing cross that was met on the volley by the onrushing, sliding Ba from close range. He only directed it straight at Friedel, but luckily the Tottenham goalkeeper''s momentum was such that he ended up bundling the ball over the line with him. Is that an own goal then?</p><!-- Block 44 --><p><strong>49 min:</strong> After the goal, there was some pushing and shoving between Cabaye and Livermore. Something about nothing. "Is Selma Blair in Cerebus?" asks Ian Copestake, for whom the restraining order is in the post.</p><!-- Block 45 --><p><strong>51 min:</strong> Adebayor is being booed for being fouled. "An Asian footy fan here," says Kamto Wong. "The game might be a bit dull, but I''d rather watch this game then the Manyoo/Chelsea/Real/Barca etc one-sided "bore-fest" they try to force down our neck every weekend." Do you hear, Ian Ayre? <strong>Do you hear</strong>?</p><!-- Block 46 --><p><strong>52 min:</strong> Adebayor goes so close to restoring Tottenham''s lead within a matter of minutes. The chance came from exceptional play from Modric, who ghosted through midfield and then scooped a superb pass in between the two Taylors for Adebayor, who had stayed onside. His first touch took him away from goal, but from an angle on the right, his shot went through Steven Taylor''s legs and slithered just past the far post with Krul rooted to the spot.</p><!-- Block 47 --><p><strong>54 min:</strong> We''ve got a game on our hands now and not before time.</p><!-- Block 48 --><p><strong>55 min:</strong> "Well done Besty," shouts Pardew. "Superb." I can''t recall Best touching the ball.</p><!-- Block 49 --><p><strong>56 min:</strong> Bassong''s clearing header only finds Obertan around 30 yards from goal. He comes inside and then sends a low, swerving effort a few yards wide of Friedel''s left post.</p><!-- Block 50 --><p><strong>58 min:</strong> Lee Probert is the most unpopular man in Newcastle right now. Ryan Taylor stops playing on the left flank, assuming the ball had gone out for a throw-in - it had, but play to the whistle - and Modric skips past him, marauds into the area, bides his time and then cuts the ball back to Van der Vaart, who stabs a shot straight at Krul. More boos, more anger. And this time they have a point, although it was the <del>assistant referee''s</del> linesman''s fault.</p><!-- Block 51 --><p><strong>60 min:</strong> "No more boos for the ref from Newcastle fans I hope since he managed to dispossess Spurs in the build up to that goal," sighs Sam Abrahams.</p><!-- Block 52 --><p><strong>61 min:</strong> Kyle Walker could be the second Spurs player to go off injured. "He''s certainly a walker at the moment, not a runner," honks Martin Tyler. That''s quite a good one actually.</p><!-- Block 53 --><p><strong>63 min:</strong> It''s that time of the day: Rafael van der Vaart is going to be replaced by Jermain Defoe. Has he ever finished a game for Spurs?</p><!-- Block 54 --><p><strong>65 min:</strong> Tottenham''s midfield does lack balance without Aaron Lennon and they don''t really have a replacement for him.</p><!-- Block 55 --><p><strong>GOAL! Newcastle 1-2 Tottenham (Defoe, 68 min):</strong> Well he didn''t need long. Just after Krul had denied Defoe a goal with his first touch by beating him to Parker''s defence-splitting pass, he puts Tottenham ahead with his next touch. This time Parker did find him with a pass from the left. He was outside the area and had his back to goal, but with Ryan Taylor caught on the wrong side of him, Defoe was able to spin in one movement and then crack a brilliant low shot into the bottom-right corner with his lesser-used left foot. That all happened in a flash. He''s so sharp.</p><!-- Block 56 --><p><strong>70 min:</strong> Modric lobs a pass over the top for Defoe, who looked offside. The flag stays down, but from a tight angle he can only whack a harmless shot into the side netting. Newcastle respond with two changes. Hatem Ben Arfa and Shola Ameobi are on, Demba Ba and Leon Best are off.</p><!-- Block 57 --><p><strong>72 min: </strong>Here he is. "I''ve been at the theatre and now must use some different big words in a review," says Gary Naylor. Get you. "It is Selma and not Tony with whom Mr Copestake is so taken isn''t it?"</p><!-- Block 58 --><p><strong>73 min:</strong> Bale chips a cross towards Adebayor, who looks poised to head home and seal the game, only for Coloccini to lean in and knock him over. That could easily have been another penalty. The ball comes to Modric on the right goal-line, but it''s too tight for him to work another opening and Newcastle survive.</p><!-- Block 59 --><p><strong>75 min:</strong> Scott Parker is booked for fouling Ameobi on the right. It wasn''t a bad foul, but he''s been a persistent offender.</p><!-- Block 60 --><p><strong>76 min:</strong> "It''s not bad watching this match as text," says Oliver Mallah. That''s the high standard we try to achieve: not bad. "But every now and then, when I refresh it on my phone I get relegated to the past. It reverts to several minutes before." If you''re a Newcastle fan, that could be a good thing. Ah, for the bliss of before the 68th minute.</p><!-- Block 61 --><p><strong>77 min:</strong> Newcastle throw on Davide Santon for Danny Simpson, a like-for-like swap.</p><!-- Block 62 --><p><strong>78 min:</strong> Tiote wallops Modric with a Rooney of a challenge. He''s booked, which is probably just about right.</p><!-- Block 63 --><p><strong>79 min:</strong> Walker goes for the spectacular with a volley from miles out. No.</p><!-- Block 64 --><p><strong>80 min:</strong> Ben Arfa finds a pocket of space for the first time and tees up Obertan for a cross from the right, but his low centre is too close to Friedel.</p><!-- Block 65 --><p><strong>81 min:</strong> Tiote tries a first-time curler from 25 yards out, but although it''s cleanly hit, it''s right above Friedel, who pushes over for a corner, which is headed away.</p><!-- Block 66 --><p><strong>82 min:</strong> Newcastle are doing everything they can to find an equaliser. They now have a free-kick just outside the Spurs area after Parker''s foul on Tiote...</p><!-- Block 67 --><p><strong>83 min:</strong> It looked like it was made for the left foot of Ben Arfa. Instead Ryan Taylor takes it with his right and curls it around the wall, only for Friedel to beat it aside at his near post.</p><!-- Block 68 --><p><strong>84 min:</strong> Clownish play from Adebayor stops Spurs from wrapping the game up. After a Tottenham break, he picked up possession on the edge of the area. He had Defoe free to his left but instead of playing him in, he tried to go it alone and ran into traffic. Selfish. "I''d be more impressed if Ian Copestake was obsessed with Lionel Blair rather than his long lost cousin Selma," says Ian Burch. Who says he isn''t?</p><!-- Block 69 --><p><strong>GOAL! Newcastle 2-2 Tottenham (Ameobi, 86 min):</strong> Adebayor is made to pay for his selfishness moments ago in the most clinical style. Tottenham were under pressure and Parker tried to alleviate it by booting the ball away from danger. However he only got height on it rather than distance, the ball going to Tiote outside the area. He knocked it to his left for Cabaye, who instantly cushioned a fine pass through to Ameobi. Clear of his marker, he took the ball on to his left foot, and then from around 16 yards out he cracked an unstoppable low shot into the far corner, past the despairing dive by Friedel. What a brilliant finish.</p><!-- Block 70 --><p><strong>88 min:</strong> Incredible! Straight after Newcastle''s equaliser, Krul is called upon to stop Defoe winning it for Spurs. He broke into the area, and although his first shot was blocked by Coloccini, the ball fell kindly to him, but Krul parried away his follow-up effort.</p><!-- Block 71 --><p><strong>89 min:</strong> Adebayor is replaced by Roman Pavlyuchenko.</p><!-- Block 72 --><p><strong>90 min:</strong> There will be five minutes of stoppage time.</p><!-- Block 73 --><p><strong>90 min+2:</strong> What a double miss from Coloccini! Modric was booked for a foul on the left that gave Newcastle a free-kick. Ryan Taylor bent it in beautifully and Coloccini broke clear of his marker, only to somehow direct his volley from six yards out away from goal! It almost served as an assist for Ameobi, who couldn''t react quickly enough. The ball was eventually poked back to Coloccini, who turned and smashed the ball wide of the right post! What a pulsating ending.</p><!-- Block 74 --><p><strong>90 min+3:</strong> Gutierrez''s strong run leads to a chance for him to shoot from the edge of the area, but his weak drive is blocked and Tottenham hack it clear with some difficulty.</p><!-- Block 75 --><p><strong>90 min+5:</strong> On the left, Ameobi tricks his way past two challenges and then tries to cross. It''s blocked by Livermore, and the cries for handball are vociferous - and ignored by Lee Probert!</p><!-- Block 76 --><p><strong>90 min+6:</strong> One last chance for Newcastle but Gutierrez''s low sighter is straight at Friedel.</p><!-- Block 77 --><p><strong>Peep! Peep! Peep!</strong> And there''s the final whistle. Phew, what a cracking end to that match. The ball did strike Livermore on the left arm, but it was ball to hand. Neither side really deserved to win, although Tottenham will feel they should have done, not least because they twice gave away the lead. Newcastle remain unbeaten. It''s not hard to work out why. Thanks for reading and emailing. Bye.</p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/football&k=Premier+League+2011-12&k=Newcastle+United&k=Tottenham+Hotspur&k=Football&k=Sport" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/football/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/football/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=Newcastle+United+v+Tottenham+Hotspur+-+as+it+happened+%7C+Jacob+Steinberg+Article+1648348&ch=Football&c2=60753&c4=Premier+League+2011-12%2CNewcastle+United+%28Football%29%2CTottenham+Hotspur+%28Football%29%2CFootball%2CSport&c3=guardian.co.uk&c6=Jacob+Steinberg&c7=11-Oct-16&c8=1648348&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: football/2011/oct/16/newcastle-united-tottenham-hotspur-live|2011-10-16T21:13:26+01:00|510c09c1419f20f4fba1f71b0670fef9826b000c -->', NULL, 'Football', 'guardian.co.uk', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:29'),
