(475, 4, 'guard_645adb67efb4bccaa9092c2b51cd4930', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2011/oct/16/yemen-protest-rally-saleh', 'Six killed in Yemen protest rally', 'Tom Finn in Sana''a', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2011/10/16/1318784167233/Anti-government-protests--003.jpg', '2011-10-16 18:59:15', NULL, 'Snipers open fire at protesters calling for President Ali Abdullah Saleh''s resignation in Sana''a', '<p>Six people were shot dead in Yemen on Sunday, including a 20-year-old woman, when plain-clothes government loyalists launched a sniper attack on a rally in  Sana''a calling for President Ali Abdullah Saleh''s resignation.</p><p>Sunday''s bloodshed follows a brutal assault by government troops on a previous rally in the capital on Saturday, heightening fears that the impoverished country may be heading towards civil war.</p><p>Witnesses said Saturday''s demonstration was dispersed when plain-clothed snipers opened fire on them from nearby rooftops as they approached Zubayri street, a strategic intersection controlled by the Republican Guard, an elite force headed by the president''s son Ahmed.</p><p>"We didn''t see any soldiers, we just heard gunshots coming from the houses all around us," said Ahmed Bin Mubarak, a professor of business administration at Sana''a University. "After that I saw men slumped on the ground in pools of blood."</p><p>The violence escalated when a division of defected soldiers who had been flanking the demonstrators started returning fire with automatic weapons. Protesters say they were caught in the middle as the two sides hurled mortars and anti-aircraft missiles at each other.</p><p>"Most of the dead protesters were shot in the back of the head or the neck," said Mohammed al-Qubati, a surgeon directing operations at a makeshift hospital in Change Square. "There is no doubt in my mind that they were shooting to kill."</p><p>Among the corpses were four civilians and two soldiers from the 1st armoured division, headed by renegade army general Ali Mohsin al-Ahmar who defected to the opposition in March. For decades Mohsin served as the regime''s iron fist, helping Saleh win a bloody civil war in 1994 against the south. Despite defecting, he still has access to nearly half of the country''s military resources and assets. Protesters who had previously touted Mohsin''s soldiers as ''heroes and protectors of the revolution'' have started to express their apprehension with some claiming that their presence is derailing their peaceful protest movement.</p><p>"We had no say in this. Ali Mohsin and his solders are giving them more of a justification for the crackdown," said Ahmed Al-Sarbi, a 24-year-old activist.</p><p>Tensions between the protesters and soldiers spilled over for the first time on Sunday when a group of Mohsin''s men tried to force their way past a line of volunteers in to the field hospital in search of one of their men.</p><p>Yemen''s deputy information minister Abdou Janadi said Sunday''s casualties were "unfortunate" but went on to accuse Mohsin of provoking the clashes and using the protesters as a human shield.</p><p>In a defiant televised speech on Sunday evening Saleh said Yemen was witnessing an attempted "military-islamic coup" and that the "military and police forces would bear on their shoulders responsibility for the future of the homeland."</p><p>Yemenis are waiting for UN security council members to agree to a resolution expected to urge Saleh to hand over power in return for immunity from prosecution. Britain drafted the resolution in consultation with France and the US and intends to circulate it to the 15-nation security council on Tuesday.</p><p>Protesters have called for decisive action from the security council. Many in the anti-Saleh camp accuse both Riyadh and Washington of continuing to support Saleh, who had once been their ally against Al-Qaeda in Yemen-based wing. They accuse the west of adopting double standards by supporting the pro-democracy uprising in Libya but not in Yemen.</p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/world&k=Yemen&k=Arab+and+Middle+East+unrest&k=Middle+East&k=World+news" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/world/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/world/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=Six+killed+in+Yemen+protest+rally+Article+1648407&ch=World+news&c2=60753&c4=Yemen+%28News%29%2CArab+and+Middle+East+unrest+%28News%29%2CMiddle+East+%28News%29%2CWorld+news&c3=The+Guardian&c6=Tom+Finn+in+Sana%27a&c7=11-Oct-16&c8=1648407&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: world/2011/oct/16/yemen-protest-rally-saleh|2011-10-16T21:13:29+01:00|ae8e9f769b0362caf84555401e4f4da7d24cce73 -->', NULL, 'World news', 'The Guardian', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:32'),
(476, 4, 'guard_9f552a6774caf16e5a4f5ae241d095ef', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/artanddesign/2011/oct/16/history-of-british-fireworks-exhibition', 'The sparkling history of British fireworks', 'Maev Kennedy', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/online/2011/10/16/1318780479894/Fireworks-posters-001.jpg', '2011-10-16 18:59:44', NULL, 'Thanks to one man''s collection, a new exhibition explores our relationship with man-made magic that lights up the sky', '<p>It is the most ephemeral of crafts, and something the British used to be quite good at. We do, after all, have a day in November devoted to it.</p><p>Britain used to make some of the most dazzling domestic fireworks in the world, but the homegrown industry fizzled out decades ago as China took over.</p><p>However, one last shower of golden sparks and ruby stars are exploding from Britain''s lost fireworks makers, with the first exhibition devoted to them and our relationship with their magical products.</p><p>The Compton Verney gallery, near Stratford, Warwickshire, currently contains the life''s work of Maurice Evans, 82, a retired scrap metal dealer and pyrotechnician who filled his home in Sussex with fireworks, posters, photographs and shop displays.</p><p>His collection has not only familiar rockets and catherine wheels but also fireworks in the shape of petrol pumps, thatched cottages, soldiers and sailors.</p><p>The exhibition traces the origins of fireworks in Britain back to the lavish public displays of the 18th and 19th centuries.</p><p>A poster for a display at Tenterden, Kent, in March 1863 celebrating the marriage of the Prince of Wales and Princess Alexandra promised "a rich display of Danish fire", a "Chinese palm tree", and "a display of artifical moonlight".<br /><br />When Evans, now aged 82, was a child, Guy Fawkes night was torture. He suffered badly from asthma and was never allowed out to see the bonfire and fireworks. Instead he was penned up at home hearing the bangs and seeing the distant flashes.</p><p>As a teenager he roamed the nearby army ranges with friends, searching for unexploded ordnance; one pyrotechnical experiment cost him a finger, but did nothing to stop his craving to see explosions.</p><p>Evans was in his twenties when he started to buy examples of every type of new firework and advertising he could find.</p><p>Evans''s collection, which has been given to the Museum of British Folklore, represents the lost era of British fireworks with long forgotten names such as Wizard, Lion, Britannia, Excelsior, Hammonds, Rainbow, Wessex, the Invicta Sparkler, the Astra Floodlight, and Attaboy – "the newest banger".</p><p>That history began to be lost decades ago. After the second world war scores of small factories sprang up in isolated rural areas making domestic fireworks. But the mass import of Chinese fireworks, made far cheaper than they could be in Britain, all but ended the industry.</p><p>Display fireworks are still designed and made in Britain, but all domestic fireworks are now imported.</p><p>Simon Costin, who designed the exhibition, believes the exhibits reveal a lost world. "Most of [them] are now unique survivors, the only evidence of the thousands of men and women who made the fireworks by hand, and the anonymous geniuses who designed and painted the advertising and packaging," he said.</p><p>Costin is also director of the Museum of British Folklore, the peripatetic museum to which Evans has donated his entire collection.</p><p>Art historian Steven Parissien, director of the Compton Vernon gallery, who spent part of his childhood living over his father''s shoe shop, next door to a sweetshop that occasionally gave him free fireworks. In front of him is a box of fireworks in the shape of apples and oranges.</p><p>"Exploding fruit," he said. "Who wouldn''t give anything to see an exploding apple?"</p><p><em>Remember, remember: A history of fireworks in Britain, is at the Compton Verney gallery until 11 December </em></p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/artanddesign&k=Exhibitions&k=Art&k=Art+and+design&k=UK+news" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/artanddesign/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/artanddesign/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=The+sparkling+history+of+British+fireworks+Article+1648387&ch=Art+and+design&c2=60753&c4=Exhibitions%2CArt+%28visual+arts+only%29%2CArt+and+design%2CUK+news&c3=The+Guardian&c6=Maev+Kennedy&c7=11-Oct-16&c8=1648387&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: artanddesign/2011/oct/16/history-of-british-fireworks-exhibition|2011-10-16T21:13:29+01:00|bfa00a6e156b564505490a8b0af9c0c42abcb81d -->', NULL, 'Art and design', 'The Guardian', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:32'),
(477, 4, 'guard_073547354d71785f791f2557d8cf8aac', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/stage/2011/oct/16/sixty-six-books-review', 'Sixty-Six Books – review', 'Michael Billington', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Arts/Arts_/Pictures/2011/10/16/1318774338816/Catherine-Tate-in-Sixty-S-003.jpg', '2011-10-16 19:00:00', NULL, 'Josie Rourke''s marathon curtain-raiser for the new Bush theatre varied widely in tone and quality, writes <strong>Michael Billington</strong>', '<p>I confess that this is a partial response to&nbsp;the vast enterprise with which Josie Rourke has chosen to christen the spaciously handsome new Bush theatre. The event consists of 66 responses, in the form of plays, poems&nbsp;and song, to the books of the King James Bible. But, although I retired&nbsp;from the initial 24-hour showing&nbsp;after seeing a mere nine of the&nbsp;plays, I feel free to offer a few general observations.</p><p>One is that, in a world where the Bible&nbsp;is less part of the common culture than The X Factor, some of the responses carry little weight: what, for&nbsp;instance, is one to make of Daisy Hasan''s translation of Joshua into a hip Judaic proselytiser in modern India, unless one has recently read the original? Multiple authorship also leads&nbsp;to enormous divergencies in tone&nbsp;and quality: it is disconcerting to move from the flip jokiness of Jeanette Winterson''s response to Genesis, in which Catherine Tate reads out God''s tweets on earth''s formation, to the awestruck, if diffuse, poem that is Anne Michaels''s answer to Exodus.</p><p>The pieces that work are those that seize on a single story or incorporate some of the original biblical language. Neil Bartlett movingly uses the fable of Balaam and his Ass both to recall his boyhood memories and to underline the revelation that comes from seeing life from the perspectives of others. In Beardy, Tom Wells wittily turns the Samson of Judges into a circus strong-man besotted by the bearded lady and ready to bring the big tent tumbling down. Best of all is Stella Duffy''s response to the Book of Ruth, in which the heroine and her mother-in-law, Naomi, are portrayed as two resilient women surviving loss and loneliness together in an alien land: as played by Kate Duchêne and Nikki Amuka-Bird, under Philip Wilson''s direction, this becomes a powerful testament to sisterhood.</p><p>Obviously, there is a lot I never got to&nbsp;see: Neil LaBute''s answer to Job, Tim Rice''s lyric responding to Chronicles 2 and Rowan Williams''s reaction to Lazarus. But although this is a big, bold enterprise that it is perfectly possible to see in smaller, evening-long chunks, I question the whole notion of a 24-hour marathon. You wouldn''t attempt to read the Bible in a day, so the attempt to encompass everything from Genesis to Revelation in a single theatrical arc strikes me as perverse: it allows little time for reflection and, even after two-and-a-half hours, left me feeling subject to sustained oral bombardment. I will, however, say one thing for the venture: it makes you want to go to the book.</p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/stage&k=Theatre&k=The+Bible&k=Stage&k=Culture" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/stage/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/stage/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=Sixty-Six+Books+%E2%80%93+review+Article+1648358&ch=Stage&c2=60753&c4=Theatre%2CThe+Bible%2CStage%2CCulture&c3=The+Guardian&c6=Michael+Billington&c7=11-Oct-16&c8=1648358&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: stage/2011/oct/16/sixty-six-books-review|2011-10-16T21:13:29+01:00|1f9e7574d94e7130b646cb6f0d0a7e8478ae9b7e -->', NULL, 'Stage', 'The Guardian', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:32'),
(478, 4, 'guard_c79bf9785be1b8aa6fdf534db9b876b4', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2011/oct/16/west-bromwich-albion-wolverhampton-wanderers1', 'West Bromwich Albion 2-0 Wolverhampton Wanderers | Premier League match report', 'Stuart James at The Hawthorns', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Football/Pix/pictures/2011/10/16/1318780989866/Peter-Odemwingie-celebrat-003.jpg', '2011-10-16 19:01:19', NULL, 'Chris Brunt and Peter Odemwingie took advantage of Wolves'' defensive vulnerabilities to give West Bromwich Albion their first home win of the season', '<p>The bright start that Wolverhampton Wanderers made to the season is beginning to feel like a trick of the mind. Mick McCarthy''s side slumped to a fifth straight league defeat here – their worst run in the top flight since 1984, when they were relegated – as goals from Chris Brunt and Peter Odemwingie secured their Black Country rivals a much-needed victory of their own that lifted them out of the relegation zone.</p><p>Wolves had no shortage of possession, especially in the opening 45 minutes, but the absence of a cutting edge was every bit as glaring as the defensive vulnerability that West Bromwich Albion ruthlessly exposed with some classic counter-attacking in their first home win of the season.</p><p>The Albion supporters were jumping the gun when they chanted "You''re getting sacked in the morning," as McCarthy looked on forlornly from the touchline, but tThere is no disputing that these are worrying times for the Wolves manager. After collecting two wins and a draw from their opening three matches, they have failed to pick up a point since. "It''s my team. It''s my responsibility," McCarthy said. "But it''s no more pressure than I''ve been under normally."</p><p>McCarthy was unhappy with Paul Scharner, the Albion midfielder, whom he accused of "taking the piss", after the Austrian angered Stephen Hunt and Stephen Ward by lifting his shirt late on in the game to reveal a top that McCarthy seemed to think carried a message.</p><p>"I don''t know what it said on it but it was obviously something that annoyed Wardy at the time," said McCarthy. "I''m all right with them having a backheel but it''s kind of taking the piss and rubbing people''s noses in it [to do that with the shirt] when you''re getting beaten."</p><p>Scharner disputed that he was guilty of anything inflammatory. "My kids gave it to me, it''s just a T-shirt with a big Albion logo on it and that''s what I showed to the supporters," he said.</p><p>Wolves have bigger issues to worry about. They face Swansea City at home on Saturday and will have to show a marked improvement at both ends of the pitch if they are to get out of their current rut. Roger Johnson was particularly poor here and will be keen to see the back of the outstanding Shane Long, whose movement and pace troubled the Wolves captain throughout.</p><p>Wolves fell behind in the eighth minute. Billy Jones, who impressed on his Premier League debut, ran on to Youssouf Mulumbu''s pass before expertly cutting the ball back for Brunt to sweep home. Kevin Doyle came close to equalising six minutes later, when Jonas Olsson blocked superbly, and Johnson squandered a decent headed chance midway through the second half.</p><p>West Bromwich, however, always looked menacing when they broke upfield and it was no surprise when they added a second goal, Scharner''s neat backheel inviting Odemwingie, who has endured a difficult start to the season and had only come off the substitutes'' bench four minutes earlier, to drill into the bottom corner. "The goal will be good for him," Roy Hodgson, the Albion manager, said. "It''s important for him that he realises that we''re all 100 per cent behind him and that we don''t expect him to shoulder the whole burden to keep us in the league."</p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/football&k=Premier+League+2011-12&k=West+Brom&k=Wolverhampton+Wanderers&k=Football&k=Sport" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/football/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/football/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=West+Bromwich+Albion+2-0+Wolverhampton+Wanderers+%7C+Premier+League+match+report+Article+1648397&ch=Football&c2=60753&c4=Premier+League+2011-12%2CWest+Brom+%28Football%29%2CWolverhampton+Wanderers+%28Football%29%2CFootball%2CSport&c3=The+Guardian&c6=Stuart+James+at+The+Hawthorns&c7=11-Oct-16&c8=1648397&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: football/2011/oct/16/west-bromwich-albion-wolverhampton-wanderers1|2011-10-16T21:13:29+01:00|4a5000a5876959c336053fac00e8e65afd629b1a -->', NULL, 'Football', 'The Guardian', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:32');
