(479, 4, 'guard_2da00da9f657225894e380ba426359aa', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2011/oct/16/newcastle-united-tottenham-hotspur-premier-league', 'Newcastle United 2-2 Tottenham Hotspur | Premier League match report', 'Kevin McCarra at St James'' Park', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Football/Pix/pictures/2011/10/16/1318784220787/Demba-Ba-003.jpg', '2011-10-16 19:13:31', NULL, 'Shola Ameobi scored an 86th-minute equaliser as Newcastle and Spurs drew 2-2 at St James'' Park', '<p>A shared craving for improvement prevented either side from getting the better of the other. Newcastle United and Tottenham Hotspur ought not to be separated even in their satisfaction, even though a team held to a draw on their own ground would usually be crestfallen. Alan Pardew''s side, however, maintained their unbeaten record despite being required to equalise twice. At present Newcastle are bringing encouragement to a St James'' Park crowd whose spirit can be officially certified unbreakable after so many years of crashing anticlimax.</p><p>Given time, Tottenham will be able to look beyond the late leveller from the substitute Shola Ameobi. There was still merit in a display that had enterprise and even an air of durability for much of the game. It was regrettable that Ledley King should have to go off injured in the first half but even if there was no clean sheet on this occasion Spurs have long since understood that it would be absurd to waste their lives agonising over his condition.</p><p>There is cause for solidly based hope at Tottenham. The club is inclined to brood on matters such as the limitation of its White Hart Lane home as a revenue generator but Harry Redknapp does still have a squad with depth in some areas. Indeed, this fixture, as an open and exhausting contest, was ideal for the introduction of Jermain Defoe, who then gave the visitors a 2-1 advantage. It will be a gruelling assignment for Redknapp''s side to finish in the top four but they are better equipped than he often implies.</p><p>If there is any unease in the mind of the Spurs manager it will concern the fact that half a dozen league goals have been conceded in four away games. There was a sense here that Newcastle could not be stopped in their tracks with the considerable presence of Cheik Tioté in the centre of midfield. There was a certain lack of vigilance and, in consequence, Tottenham could never completely drain the hope from St James'' Park spectators who had no cause to suppose their side were doomed.</p><p>It somehow felt natural that Ameobi should level the scores with a spectacular drive in the 86th minute, after a flick from Yohan Cabaye. This game might as well have been designed as an examination of Newcastle''s perseverance. They fell behind after 40 minutes because of lapses in concentration. Pardew''s side could have survived the incident after Cabaye lost possession, but Steven Taylor made an unnecessary challenge on Emmanuel Adebayor, who was running towards the wing rather than the posts. Rafael van der Vaart showed a far greater sense of direction than the centre-back when tucking the spot-kick beyond Tim Krul.</p><p>Adversity, however, prodded Newcastle into effectiveness. Demba Ba levelled after 48 minutes. At that stage the loss of King had been barely noticed by Tottenham. That event was swamped by the general inconsequentiality of the action. The goal, however, saw Jonás Gutiérrez tear past Luka Modric and Kyle Walker, with Brad Friedel getting to Ba''s volley but grasping it when the ball was behind the line.</p><p>The early insipidness of the match seemed merely to have been saving its hoard of incident for the latter stages. Adebayor was close to restoring Tottenham''s lead with an effort, following service from Modric, that went marginally beyond the far post. Van der Vaart was soon to crash a drive straight at Krul.</p><p>Van der Vaart would be replaced by a more natural predator in Defoe, who put Tottenham in front once more, finishing a ball from Modric. No one could quibble if either manager saw this as a contest where fallibility was on the rise. The unstable action might have indicated that neither side should expect too much of this campaign but the fixture itself was absorbing precisely because of the accidents and pervasive fallibility.</p><p>There was scope, above all, for the predatory Defoe. Tottenham may lack the means of some clubs in the upper reaches of the table but an away draw of this sort suggests a purpose and organisation that will keep them to the fore, even if they will rue the fact that they could not hold tight to the lead for those closing minutes. Newcastle, for their part, are far from despair.</p><p>Most people can recall a grandiosity of intent that once saw the club spend heavily without quite getting the return on investment anticipated. The drama too often left an ache in the hearts of supporters. This is a less histrionic period and perhaps those fans will be left with a modest satisfaction.</p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/football&k=Premier+League+2011-12&k=Newcastle+United&k=Tottenham+Hotspur&k=Football&k=Sport" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/football/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/football/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=Newcastle+United+2-2+Tottenham+Hotspur+%7C+Premier+League+match+report+Article+1648413&ch=Football&c2=60753&c4=Premier+League+2011-12%2CNewcastle+United+%28Football%29%2CTottenham+Hotspur+%28Football%29%2CFootball%2CSport&c3=The+Guardian&c6=Kevin+McCarra+at+St+James%27+Park&c7=11-Oct-16&c8=1648413&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: football/2011/oct/16/newcastle-united-tottenham-hotspur-premier-league|2011-10-16T21:13:29+01:00|94290c62f8d850711239ded67905d843a86cd75d -->', NULL, 'Football', 'The Guardian', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:32'),
(480, 4, 'guard_606d3b36a6125f5b5feb96759eb59b19', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2011/oct/16/sco-ticciati-suckling-review', 'SCO/Ticciati/Suckling – review', 'Kate Molleson', NULL, '2011-10-16 19:15:01', NULL, 'Mark Suckling''s new piece coupled fierce intellect with the musical sensibility of a fine violinist, writes <strong>Kate Molleson</strong>', '<p>Hebridean psalm singing and chaos theory, Jorge Luis Borges and the harmonic overtone series. Unlikely bedfellows, but Martin Suckling fuses these influences and more into his engrossing, haunting and self-assured storm, rose, tiger. The Glasgow-born composer has been earmarked as an emerging talent; this latest work, written for the Scottish Chamber Orchestra, confirms the distinctness of&nbsp;his voice. It couples fierce intellect with the musical sensibility of a fine violinist, and offers a generous hand to&nbsp;listeners by keeping earthy hooks at&nbsp;the core of its clever tricks. The final&nbsp;resounding passacaglia strays toward filmic, but weird micro-tuning&nbsp;and fuzzy layering keep us on our&nbsp;toes.</p><p>Only a week into the new season, and&nbsp;the SCO is already sounding well&nbsp;warmed up. Principal conductor Robin Ticciati continues to push for transparent, spacious and classically articulated playing, even (and particularly effectively) in postclassical repertoire. He tests the balance between&nbsp;broad scale and careful nuance,&nbsp;which here brought out the thrill and madness in Schumann''s Fourth Symphony – as it had in last week''s season opener, Berlioz''s Symphonie Fantastique. Occasionally, a&nbsp;gesture jars a bit as over-done or half-baked. But more often, the risk-taking reveals inner parts you never knew were there, and prompts alert playing more akin to a big chamber group than a small orchestra.</p><p>Maybe it''s hard for visiting soloists to&nbsp;feel part of this cosy Ticciati-SCO bond, but Viktoria Mullova seemed to make little effort. Reading Beethoven''s Violin Concerto from the score while Ticciati conducted from memory, she grafted her lines on to the orchestra rather than joining them. Her sound was&nbsp;frosty, her attacks hurried and hard-edged; only the tuttis had a conspiring warmth to them. Mullova has&nbsp;a reputation for iciness that she didn''t do much to thaw here.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/music&k=Classical+music&k=Robert+Schumann&k=Ludwig+van+Beethoven&k=Music&k=Culture" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/music/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/music/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=SCO%2FTicciati%2FSuckling+%E2%80%93+review+Article+1648361&ch=Music&c2=60753&c4=Classical+music+%28Music+genre%29%2CRobert+Schumann%2CLudwig+van+Beethoven%2CMusic%2CCulture&c3=The+Guardian&c6=Kate+Molleson&c7=11-Oct-16&c8=1648361&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: music/2011/oct/16/sco-ticciati-suckling-review|2011-10-16T21:13:29+01:00|2d97df2800782787a2e0d17c8944464ffe6bbe4c -->', NULL, 'Music', 'The Guardian', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:32'),
(481, 4, 'guard_650cc7dbaab2826d532e01ae7d5ad3a4', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2011/oct/16/demolition-of-gaddafi-compound-begins', 'Bulldozers begin demolition of Gaddafi''s Tripoli compound', 'Associated Press', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/10/16/1318785603525/gaddafi-compound-demoliti-003.jpg', '2011-10-16 19:20:56', NULL, 'Knocking down Gaddafi''s Tripoli stronghold is seen by revolutionaries as erasing ''symbol of repression''', '<!-- Redistribution rights for this field are unavailable -->', NULL, 'World news', 'The Guardian', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:32'),
(482, 4, 'guard_efdab69d3e138add3e9cda09219882ac', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/organgrinder/2011/oct/16/rupert-murdoch-news-corp-dan-sabbagh', 'Why Rupert Murdoch needs to move his family to the News Corp sidelines', 'Dan Sabbagh', NULL, '2011-10-16 19:27:00', NULL, '<strong>Dan Sabbagh:</strong> There are obstacles ahead if James Murdoch ends up running the company', '<p>Rupert Murdoch hasn''t got to running a $33bn media group just by giving up at the first sign of resistance. This week''s annual meeting may be on the Fox studio lot in Los Angeles, but there will only be a limited amount of drama. He sits on 40% of the votes, and while there are small shareholders in revolt, they are hardly likely to force change. Nor does it help that some of their demands are just plain daft: asking for 13 out of 15 directors to quit would leave nobody experienced in charge of the company. And above all, if you are judging on financial performance, what''s not to like? Operating profit (after stripping out some massive legal costs) was up 12%, and the voting shares are bouncing back from their post hacking lows from $14 in August to $17.27 at the time of writing.</p><p>The conclusion the Fox-to-Times conglomerate wants to draw is what it has always done: ignore the critics. There was serious talk inside the company a year ago about Murdoch splitting the chairman and chief executive roles, but this has gone away. A new non-executive director might join the board to fill the spot Elisabeth Murdoch was meant to take up, but this is hardly radical stuff. Yet, there ought to be a little more change than that, because the corporate problems are not over either.</p><p>The easy assumption had always been that James Murdoch would end up running the company, although in truth it is hard to think of an equivalent public company of similar size that would simply pass down the family line. If he does take over, how long is he supposed to be in charge? Another 40 years? And is it proven that James is as brilliant as his father? There is no shortage of obstacles ahead.</p><p>James Murdoch has to go before the culture select committee in the first half of November. It is likely that he can cook up a good explanation as to what happened at the over-analysed meeting with Colin Myler and Tom Crone over the "for Neville" email; in effect he can say that he did not appreciate, or was not led to appreciate its significance with the benefit of hindsight. But there is no good excuse for the disastrous decision of July 2009, in which he allowed News International to respond to the initial allegations of hacking by simply accusing the Guardian of choosing to "mislead the British public". When faced with serious allegations, the only sensible response is to investigate.</p><p>There is no explanation too for the string of political misjudgments on James''s watch: the ill-timed switch from Labour to Conservative; the astonishingly pugilistic speech in Edinburgh that offered no concessions to the middle ground; the company''s decision to become intimate with politicians (whose shelf life is far shorter than media moguls) – and even the decision to turn up and complain in person at the Independent''s offices because the paper ran an advertising campaign that he did not like. Nor is it just the politics. BSkyB, under James''s rule (he is still chairman), was similarly combative: seizing shares in ITV and fighting tooth and nail to keep them; battling endlessly with the regulator over Ofcom''s plans to cut Sky Sports prices (why are higher prices good for consumers?); squeezing rivals hard to control all types of film rights.</p><p>All fair in media and war no doubt, but at some point, you need friends as well as power. For News Corp, the obvious decision is to promote number two Chase Carey soon; indeed the Murdochs may be better off as shareholders on the sidelines rather than managers taking endless hits. Don''t bet on that happening, though.</p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/media&k=Media&k=Rupert+Murdoch&k=James+Murdoch&k=News+Corporation&k=Media+business" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/media/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/media/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=Why+Rupert+Murdoch+needs+to+move+his+family+to+the+News+Corp+sidelines+Article+1648132&ch=Media&c2=60753&c4=Media%2CRupert+Murdoch+%28Media%29%2CJames+Murdoch+%28Media%29%2CNews+Corporation+%28Media%29%2CMedia+business&c3=The+Guardian&c6=Dan+Sabbagh&c7=11-Oct-16&c8=1648132&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: media/organgrinder/2011/oct/16/rupert-murdoch-news-corp-dan-sabbagh|2011-10-16T21:13:29+01:00|660b7834a733da193c36173add674bd60490104f -->', NULL, 'Media', 'The Guardian', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:32'),
