(497, 4, 'guard_e79942f5e5aae29ce9f60c19bf2592d6', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2011/oct/16/england-india-delhi', 'England must learn fast if they are to keep pace with India in Delhi', 'Mike Selvey in Delhi', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Sport/Pix/columnists/2011/10/16/1318788589772/Englands-Kevin-Pietersen--003.jpg', '2011-10-16 20:11:41', NULL, 'England need to perform much better in Delhi if they are not to lose touch with India in the one-day series', '<p>If there is one quality England have demonstrated in the past few years, although most obviously in Test cricket, it is the capacity to shrug off adversity, learn the lessons fast, and produce a considerably improved performance next time out. But on Monday, in Delhi, it will take a big reversal of fortune if they are not to go to Mohali for the third one-day international with their hopes for the five-match series hanging by a thread.</p><p>In the first match at Hyderabad, despite all the preparation over the previous 10 days, they were outplayed in all departments of the game to an alarming degree, beaten by a young side in their infancy as a unit. That Mahendra Singh Dhoni won an important toss, had first use of a pitch that was to deteriorate markedly as the game progressed, condemned England to fielding in the heat of the day, and himself played one of his finest innings cannot mask the fact that England played so poorly they might well have lost comfortably in any case.</p><p>It is not in the nature of Andy Flower in particular – a pragmatist without sentiment when it comes to the selection of his teams, to which Ian Bell might offer testament – to panic. While he has said he would not be afraid to make changes if he felt they were right, it would be unusual if at first he did not simply demand a massive improvement from those who underperformed in the first game. A chance for redemption in other words. But in the short and medium term there are several, including Craig Kieswetter, Jonathan Trott, Kevin Pietersen, and Samit Patel, who are under scrutiny and for whom this series might be make or break. In Flower''s eyes everyone deserves a fair crack, but with an increasing number of young players waiting to make the breakthrough, the opportunity will not be limitless.</p><p>In Hyderabad, India took the batting powerplay as late as was possible and used it as a launching pad for the final 15 overs. With the pitch starting to show erratic bounce and offering turn, that put the game beyond England''s reach by the halfway point. Until Dhoni and Suresh Raina came together, the bowlers had done a creditable job. There will have been an inquest, though, into how Alastair Cook handled his bowling resources once Dhoni came to the crease at the end of the 29th over. By then Graeme Swann had bowled seven of his 10 overs and Dhoni and Raina, knowing his capability, were content to see him off. Swann''s figures, well as he bowled, flattered as a result.</p><p></p><p>The timing of Swann''s overs smacked too much of a preconceived template. On Dhoni''s arrival, Cook did turn to Jade Dernbach, but he could have introduced Steven Finn, who bowled rapidly, to try to rough him up. And would Swann not have been a better option during the final 10 overs than either Patel or Ravi Bopara?</p><p>Then comes the question of length and pace. During the powerplay, when the assault started with 59 runs from five overs, England, using Tim Bresnan, Dernbach and Finn, concentrated on bowling full, getting the yorker in as often as possible. Dhoni is an expert hitter of yorkers, however. That consideration, when added to the fact that the straight boundaries at Hyderabad are much shorter than those at the sides, might have made the short ball and the slow bouncer an easier option with which to defend. Back of a length might also have exploited the low bounce although this was much more apparent in the second innings.</p><p>In fact, during the powerplay, England did not use the slower ball as much as they have done in other matches. Dernbach, who has the best repertoire, used just four in two overs (one of which produced five wides) and Bresnan three: that is seven in what proved to be 34 balls of which Dhoni received four and Raina three. Too many or too few? Only experience will provide the answer. At one time the rule of thumb was to use a variation only when other methods failed. Now bowlers try to read a batsman''s mind. Maybe at times, things just get too complicated.</p><p><strong>Teams for second ODI at Feroz Shah Kotla Ground, 10am BST</strong></p><p><strong>England</strong> (from) AN Cook (capt), C Kieswetter (wkt), IJL&nbsp;Trott, KP&nbsp;Pietersen, RS Bopara, JM Bairstow, SR Patel, TT Bresnan, GP&nbsp;Swann, JW Dernbach, ST Finn, IR Bell, SG Borthwick, CR&nbsp;Woakes.</p><p><strong>India</strong> (from) MS Dhoni (capt, wkt), P Patel, A Rahane, G&nbsp;Gambhir, V Kohli, S Raina, R Jadeja, P Kumar, R Ashwin, R Vinay Kumar, U&nbsp;Yadav, R Sharma, V Aaron, M Tiwary, S Aravind.</p><p><strong>Umpires</strong> B Bowden (NZ) and S Tarapore (Ind).</p><p><strong>Third umpire</strong> S Asnani (Ind). <strong>Match referee</strong> R Mahanama (SL).</p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/sport&k=England+in+India+2011&k=England+cricket+team&k=Sport&k=Cricket" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/sport/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/sport/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=England+must+learn+fast+if+they+are+to+keep+pace+with+India+in+Delhi+Article+1648433&ch=Sport&c2=60753&c4=England+in+India+2011%2CEngland+cricket+team%2CSport%2CCricket&c3=The+Guardian&c6=Mike+Selvey+in+Delhi&c7=11-Oct-16&c8=1648433&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: sport/2011/oct/16/england-india-delhi|2011-10-16T21:13:33+01:00|fa3351cb484a82c94c6c2965c56f52e12335bdaf -->', NULL, 'Sport', 'The Guardian', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:36'),
(498, 4, 'guard_77b02e6db6144935aeafaf61308417c7', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2011/oct/16/europe-finally-listening-to-geithner', 'Europe finally listening to Geithner', 'Phillip Inman, economics correspondent', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/cartoons/2011/10/16/1318788657436/FRANCE-BANK-G20-ECONOMY-F-003.jpg', '2011-10-16 20:12:12', NULL, 'Until a few days ago repeated predictions of doom from Tim Geithner and Barack Obama seemed to fall on deaf European ears. Now that leaders are listening, time may be too short, says <strong>Phillip Inman</strong>', '<p>There are six days to save the world. That''s according to the US treasury secretary, Tim Geithner, who told the G20 finance ministers'' summit in Paris on Saturday that only a massive firewall would protect the eurozone against contagion from a Greek default.</p><p>It''s a message that the US president, Barack Obama, and his battle-hardened finance boss have sent across the Atlantic several times in the last six weeks. Geithner has popped up in European capitals three times in that period to deliver the message in person.</p><p>Until a few days ago it was something the French and Germans closed their ears to. No amount of calls for "shock and awe" shifted their position. There was simply a stubborn refusal to define the Greek situation as anything more than a local difficulty, and definitely not a crisis.</p><p>Six days is not a long time to design a mix of insurance policies, guarantees and bank capital top-ups worth upwards of €1.5tn (£1.3tn) that are credible to the financial markets and avoid making politicians look like they have spent every last euro&nbsp;cent of taxpayer funds. There is a huge industry in trying to second-guess the direction of travel in Paris and Berlin after Nicolas Sarkozy and Angela Merkel said they would reveal a killer plan next Sunday.</p><p>What kind of insurance and guarantees are in the pipeline? How much will vulnerable banks (and other private investors) be told to write off in bad loans to Greece and how many euros must the banks find to fill the void left by these bad investments?</p><p>Hedge funds, pension funds and the super wealthy are all placing bets on how negotiations will work out. Will the euro stand or fall?</p><p>Betting against Sarkozy and Merkel cobbling together a deal is bold and risky. Most likely they will unveil a package of measures that lacks the clean lines and firepower of the "big bazooka" demanded by many economists, but will be just enough to kill the Greece problem and defend Italy, Spain, Portugal and Ireland. French and German banks, which lent billions of euros to Greece, Ireland and Portugal, will also be sheltered by the deal.</p><p>Geithner is convinced the French and Germans now recognise the problem, but reading his body language and the way he spoke about the prospects for meeting the six-day deadline, he was more circumspect. He said there was an enormous amount of detail to work through before plans would look convincing and hinted that time was running desperately short.</p><p>Geithner is also concerned that Merkel in particular is more concerned about rushing through reforms of the system before tackling the problems at the heart of the crisis. Some 38 pieces of EU legislation have either been put on the statute or are in the pipeline.</p><p>There have always been several problems with this rush to legislate, at least on this scale. First it distracts from the immediate problem of tackling the EU''s debts. It whacks banks and other financial institutions when they are already on their knees, and the legislation heaps costs on the finance industry that, in turn, hamper growth. Without banks to lend, especially to smaller companies, we have no investment.</p><p>It is this last point that most exercised Geithner. He openly warned the EU against rushing to ball-and-chain the banks and make a crisis certain.</p><p>There is a flaw to the Geithner plan of massive guarantees and insurances for Wall Street that keeps them afloat and lending, and it can be seen in a park only a stone''s throw from the New York stock exchange. The Occupy Wall Street campaigners are disgusted that propping up the banks means allowing the old rapacious bonus culture to go unreformed.</p><p>Geithner argues there are many on Wall Street who are suffering because they are paid in shares and not cash. Some US bank shares are down by a half or more since the summer. But that ignores the wider picture.</p><p>If the euro is saved, with billions more in taxpayer loans and guarantees, those bank shares will rocket and the bankers will be back in clover, more than they are already.</p><p>The US treasury secretary worries that Europe needs international investors on board, only to reckon it can win a game of chicken. When countries have borrowed so much from US pension funds, Middle Eastern petrodollar sovereign funds and the Chinese, they need private investors.</p><p>In 2008 the US treasury dared the markets to bet against the government and lost. It wants the EU to heed that experience.</p><p>Left to their own devices, traders panic, fearful on behalf of their investor clients that further losses lie just round the corner. The panic, far from being the invisible hand of the markets lauded by many right-wing economists, is a bludgeoning stick causing pain and unemployment wherever it strikes.</p><p>In these circumstances, reforms to tackle banks, brokers and investors should be delayed while protester-friendly taxes on wealth go ahead.</p><p>There is another crisis looming, possibly in only a few years. But it will come from another direction –the savings in China, Germany, Japan and the US looking to spark another asset boom. Tackling that situation poses even bigger problems for politicians.</p><p>But first we need some sustainable growth, and to avert a euro debt crisis.</p><p><em>phillip.inman@guardian.co.uk</em></p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/business&k=Economics&k=Business&k=European+debt+crisis&k=European+banks" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/business/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/business/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=Europe+finally+listening+to+Geithner+Article+1648435&ch=Business&c2=60753&c4=Economics+%28Business%29%2CBusiness%2CEuropean+debt+crisis%2CEuropean+banks+%28business%29&c3=The+Guardian&c6=Phillip+Inman%2C+economics+correspondent&c7=11-Oct-16&c8=1648435&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: business/2011/oct/16/europe-finally-listening-to-geithner|2011-10-16T21:13:33+01:00|dfcc169fd21f8220f38d82c392d8df174fa698d6 -->', NULL, 'Business', 'The Guardian', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:36'),
(499, 4, 'guard_bd032841960381123719fd5fa12477a1', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2011/oct/16/israel-settlement-isolate-arab-jerusalem', 'Israel plans new settlement of 2,600 that will isolate Arab East Jerusalem', 'Chris McGreal in Jerusalem', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/10/16/1318786049511/Settlement-building-at-Gi-003.jpg', '2011-10-16 20:13:20', NULL, 'Britain, the EU and the UN condemn Israel''s decision as provocative and a further threat to the peace process', '<p>Israel has submitted plans to build the first big Jewish settlement in the occupied territories in 25 years, in a move condemned as an "assassination" of attempts to revive peace negotiations.</p><p>A leading Israeli peace group, Peace Now, denounced the plan to build 2,600 homes at Givat Hamatos on the southern edge of Jerusalem as a "game changer" because it would virtually cut off the Arab east of the city from the rest of the occupied West Bank.</p><p>The UN, the EU and Britain joined the Palestinians in condemning the move as provocative at a time when the major powers are struggling to rekindle negotiations while the Palestinian bid for statehood is still before the UN security council.</p><p>The Palestinian leadership, which has said there can be no new talks if settlement building continues, said the plans were further evidence that Israel "wants to destroy the peace process".</p><p>Givat Hamatos would form a big part of the crescent of Jewish settlements which, in parallel with the West Bank wall and fence, has increasingly isolated East Jerusalem from the rest of the occupied territories. Israeli peace activists say the intention is to solidify Israel''s claim to all of Jerusalem and to minimise the amount of the city ceded to an independent Palestine. Work could begin as early as next year.</p><p>A fortnight ago, Israel drew strong international condemnation over plans to expand an existing settlement, Gilo, by about 1,200 homes. Meir Margalit, a leftwing member of the Jerusalem council who holds the portfolio overseeing the east of the city, said that the Givat Hamatos plan had more serious implications because, not only is it much larger but, for the first time in quarter of a century, it established a new colony.</p><p>"This is a big deal because this is a new settlement. It''s not more houses in an existing settlement but a new one that takes one of the last reserves of land remaining for the Palestinians in East Jerusalem," he said. "I don''t want to be overly dramatic but this will be that last nail in the coffin of the peace process.</p><p>"The government knows the Palestinians cannot live with this, that settlements are the most important issue for them. The people behind this are pyromaniacs and terrorists because they are lighting fires all over the place that at the end of the day will set up a new wave of terrorist attacks."</p><p>The plans were submitted for approval by Israel''s interior minister, Eli Yishai, a member of the religious, rightwing Shas party. They are likely to be backed by the prime minister, Binyamin Netanyahu, who is competing with Shas for the support of Jewish settlers and rightwing voters. Netanyahu has repeatedly said that Israel regards itself as free to build anywhere it chooses within the area it defines as Jerusalem, which cuts deeper into the West Bank since the municipal boundaries were extended after the occupation of the east of the city began in 1967.</p><p>Givat Hamatos would be the first major new Jewish settlement since Netanyahu approved the construction of nearby Har Homar in 1997, during his first term as prime minister.</p><p>The government has sought to minimise the significance of the plans by saying they have been around for several years and that no final decision has been taken. The proposal was originally drafted three years ago and then put on hold. But last week, with attention focused on the pending release of Gilat Shalit after five years captivity in Gaza, they were quietly revived and submitted for a 60-day public comment period, a last step before a final vote on approval. The decision will be made by the Jerusalem municipal council where there is broad support for settlements.</p><p>The move was welcomed by David Hershovitz, a rightwing member of the city council''s planning committee. He told the Jerusalem Post: "Givat Hamatos is a prerequisite for massive building in Jerusalem."</p><p>Saeb Erekat, the chief Palestinian negotiator, said the Givat Hamatos proposal "makes a mockery of … international efforts to bring about a just and lasting peace."</p><p>On Sunday, the British foreign secretary, William Hague, condemned "this provocative step, which further encloses East Jerusalem". Catherine Ashton, the EU foreign policy chief, described the Givat Hamatos plans as "deplorable". She said the plans undermine peace efforts by breaching Israel''s responsibility to create "an environment of trust conducive to negotiations".</p><p>The UN secretary general, Ban Ki-moon, said the Givat Hamatos plans are "contrary to international law".</p><p>"Recent developments in this regard have been unacceptable, particularly as efforts are ongoing to resume negotiations," he said.</p><p>Margalit said that he believes the government is deliberately seeking to undermine attempts to revive talks.</p><p>"From the one side, Netanyahu says he is ready to negotiate; from the other, the government does this and undermines any possibility of negotiations with the Palestinians," he said.</p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/world&k=Israel&k=Middle+East&k=World+news&k=Palestinian+territories&k=Judaism" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/world/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/world/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=Israel+plans+new+settlement+of+2%2C600+that+will+isolate+Arab+East+Jerusalem+Article+1648414&ch=World+news&c2=60753&c4=Israel+%28News%29%2CMiddle+East+%28News%29%2CWorld+news%2CPalestinian+territories+%28News%29%2CJudaism+%28News%29&c3=The+Guardian&c6=Chris+McGreal+in+Jerusalem&c7=11-Oct-16&c8=1648414&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: world/2011/oct/16/israel-settlement-isolate-arab-jerusalem|2011-10-16T21:13:33+01:00|eb04cc8fae3fb615e64a68674a2512ef7d2a956d -->', NULL, 'World news', 'The Guardian', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:36'),
(500, 4, 'guard_3f495fbd115292f6e947d2eb83c0317f', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2011/oct/16/lets-do-timeshift-tv-habits', 'Let''s do the television time-shift | Peter Preston', 'Peter Preston', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/10/16/1318767568979/Gogglebox-Britain-003.jpg', '2011-10-16 20:15:03', NULL, '<strong>Peter Preston:</strong> Technologies like Sky+ and TiVo have changed our viewing habits – and ruined TV water-cooler moments', '<p>One thing comes naturally after another. Fed up with fat Welsh tenors in fancy dress? Bored by blank-faced women slipping on wet floors and falling into the arms of no-win-no-fee lawyers (who smirk avariciously)? Can''t see the sense of more meerkats? Wonder if all that interminable BA stuff about flying and serving is supposed to mean that they''re not on strike at the moment – or that, with luck, you may still get a chilled tuna sandwich on the trip back from Prague? Then don''t just sit and groan. Fast-forward through the ads. Heaven bless what the television industry calls <a href="http://www.vodprofessional.com/news/2011q4/time-shifted-viewing-reaches-a-new-high/" title="VOD Professional - Time-Shifted Viewing Reaches a New High">time-shifted viewing</a>.</p><p>But now, it seems, this basic means of avoiding the grisliest commercial breaks is turning into a national obsession. <a href="http://www.barb.co.uk/report/index" title="BARB - BARB Reports">New figures from the Broadcasting Audience Research Bureau</a> show that non-live TV viewing, in its various forms, is breaking records week after week. A full 10% of all UK citizens who switch on a set these days watch something pre-recorded they can summon back and speed through at the press of a button. In the wonderful world of personal video recorders (PVR) some 32% of drama series and 26% of soaps are watched this way, then often thrown back into the Barb-rated accounting as Viewing on the Same Day As Live (Vosdal) statistics.</p><p>What sort of people time-shift most zealously? Young adults between 25 and 34 – and educated, professional ABC1s. Loads of Guardian readers, in short.</p><p>Enough acronyms, though. The point isn''t the jargon of the measuring trade that turns data from 5,100 households a week into a portrait of gogglebox Britain. The point is what, inexorably, time-shifting is doing to our lives. For the ads are the least part of the problem. It''s the programmes in between that need shifting too.</p><p>Take <a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/strictly-come-dancing" title="">Strictly Come Dancing</a>, on Saturday nights. Why sit through Sir Brucie''s old gags, Tess doing her twirls, sweating celebs providing two standard minutes on their training week? You can slash the padding, stick with the dancing, nip out for a pint – and still be back to carve the routines of The X Factor down to 30 minutes. Indeed, the moment somebody starts to blub, fast forward takes over as though by magic. You don''t need to suffer with the disappointed any longer. There is a better way.</p><p>And what works for weekend froth, I find, soon turns electronic escape into a wider way of televisual life. Paxman and co discuss the eurozone crisis again? Fizz. Ken Livingstone talks about press self-regulation? It''s Question Time shift time. Party political broadcasts are recorded from habit and discarded from choice. Jon Snow''s failing hospitals, <a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2011/oct/13/wayne-rooney-three-match-ban-uefa" title="The  Guardian -  Wayne Rooney handed three-match Euro 2012 ban by Uefa">Rooney''s Montenegro madness</a>, the Last Night of the Proms … all pass in a trice.</p><p>Thus television – and, indeed, much of iPlayer life – becomes not a full dress, full-on occasion, but a series of snippets cut to fill cracks. And life itself comes back to echo that snatched, unsteady state. My new Radio Times website doesn''t just tell me what is on screen today. It offers an individual selection of what I''ll like based on choices past. My media existence is pre-vetted, pre-screened, almost prescribed, courtesy of Sky+ or TiVo. I need never be challenged, absorbed or surprised again.</p><p>We talk of mass media and, sometimes, of massive media moments, of the end of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Z-Cars" title="Wikipedia - Z-Cars">Z-Cars</a> and <a href="http:///en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M*A*S*H_(TV_series)" title="Wikipedia - M*A*S*H">M*A*S*H</a>, of the Berlin Wall falling, of Live Aid and John Lennon RIP – water cooler events where office life became national life the next morning because we were all caught by a single screen experience. That''s going now: going to Vosdal or, even days after, into the general stewpot of Barb''s weekly totals. PVR on demand? It sounds somehow empowering as the habit grows, but it also leaves you feeling alone, skipping more than the ads in a fast forward world of Sky Minus.</p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/commentisfree&k=Television&k=Television+industry&k=Television&k=Media&k=Technology&k=Culture" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/commentisfree/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/commentisfree/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=Let%27s+do+the+television+time-shift+%7C+Peter+Preston+Article+1648331&ch=Comment+is+free&c2=60753&c4=Television+%28Technology%29%2CTelevision+industry+%28Media%29%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CMedia%2CTechnology%2CCulture%2CUK+news&c3=The+Guardian&c6=Peter+Preston&c7=11-Oct-16&c8=1648331&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: commentisfree/2011/oct/16/lets-do-timeshift-tv-habits|2011-10-16T21:13:33+01:00|24fba6ee22dbdc186ca1b8955c0a172006315e5c -->', NULL, 'Comment is free', 'The Guardian', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:36'),
(501, 4, 'guard_f27c63844b91c31ff11ed8caf7e12fe4', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/organgrinder/2011/oct/16/record-industry-radio-playlist', 'The record industry needs to sort out radio playlist confusion', 'Helienne Lindvall', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Media/Pix/pictures/2011/10/14/1318593391630/The-Wanted--003.jpg', '2011-10-16 20:38:01', NULL, '<strong>Helienne Lindvall:</strong> Greater transparency is needed when radio presenters face conflicts of interest', '<p>The policy of the playlist – or rather how, exactly, a single gets on it – has always been a hot topic for the record industry. Although the internet gives the public unprecedented access to music, getting playlisted on the radio is still the key way to gain exposure to a wider audience, and sell records, in the UK.</p><p>In the US, <a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/musicblog/2009/apr/16/payola-internet-radio" title="">payola – the illegal practice of paying or in any other way bribing a radio station to play your song</a> – has existed since the advent of pop music. The widespread use of payola in the 70s and 80s was described in detail in the book Hit Men, and as recently as 2005-06 <a href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/4788762.stm" title="">three of the major labels were indicted and settled out of court for pay-for-play practices</a>.</p><p>Although no such lawsuits have been launched in the UK, there have been plenty of accusations of conflict of interest when it comes to those who decide what gets played on the radio. When the dance DJ Pete Tong joined BBC Radio 1, more than 15 years ago, his day job was working as A&amp;R manager for London Records, and he was accused of favouring records signed to the label.</p><p>In 1996, Richard Park, then the programme controller of Capital Radio, formed Wildstar Records, uniting Capital Radio Group and Telstar Records in a 50-50 joint venture. Wildstar signed Craig David, who became one of the label''s biggest artists in the late 90s. Did that connection make the station more likely to playlist artists signed to the label, such as David?</p><p>Capital Radio is now owned by Global Radio, which also owns Heart, Xfm and Gold, making it a group with 20 million listeners. Global also owns an artist management company, which represents bands such as the Wanted and Cover Drive. Last year, Ofcom amended the rules for commercial TV, allowing product placement in order to implement an EU directive. It is said that some commercial radio stations lobbied for radio to be included in this section, arguing that songs played in their shows were, in effect, product placement for the artists. The music industry was horrified, suggesting that this sounded very much like payola.</p><p>Eventually Ofcom sent a clear message to the radio industry by adding clause 10.5 to its Broadcasting Code, stating: "No commercial arrangement that involves payment, or the provision of some other valuable consideration, to the broadcaster may influence the selection or rotation of music for broadcast." Breaking Ofcom rules can have serious repercussions – it can result in fines of hundreds of thousands of pounds or even having your licence revoked. Yet it''s difficult to prove the absence of payola – that an artist would have been playlisted anyway, without a financial incentive.</p><p>In 2006-07, questions surfaced regarding Jo Whiley''s choice of acts on her Radio 1 morning show. Whiley featured two high-profile live sets by the Hoosiers and the Automatic, which were both managed by her husband, Steve Morton. The sessions were included on two Live Lounge compilation CDs, which sold a combined total of 1.26m copies. The BBC said that Whiley had noted her husband''s interests on an internal register  and that she had no influence on the Radio 1 playlist and played no part in selecting songs for the Live Lounge albums.</p><p>I''m sure the reason why Global signed the Wanted to its management arm was because the band were expected to resonate with the public (young girls in particular). At the same time a station such as Capital wants to play music that resonates with its audience, so that they keep listening. That''s probably why <a href="http://comparemyradio.com/artists/The_Wanted" title="">the Wanted have been played a lot</a>. And the reason why Capital <a href=" http://comparemyradio.com/artists/One_Direction" title="">plays a similar act like One Direction (who released a single around the same time as the Wanted) a lot less</a> may very well be that Capital execs don''t believe their audience would like them as much.</p><p>Global''s legal and compliance department says: "Global does not comment on its playlist decisions and are fully compliant with the broadcasting code." But perhaps radio stations that have commercial interests in specific artists could improve transparency by sending each record considered for playlisting to an independent researcher to find out how it fares with test audiences.</p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/media&k=Radio+industry&k=BBC&k=Radio+1&k=Global+Radio&k=Commercial+radio&k=Media" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/media/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/media/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=The+record+industry+needs+to+sort+out+radio+playlist+confusion+Article+1647757&ch=Media&c2=60753&c4=Radio+industry+%28Media%29%2CBBC%2CRadio+1%2CGlobal+Radio%2CCommercial+radio+%28Media%29%2CMedia&c3=The+Guardian&c6=Helienne+Lindvall&c7=11-Oct-16&c8=1647757&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: media/organgrinder/2011/oct/16/record-industry-radio-playlist|2011-10-16T21:13:33+01:00|74be9c8410f804a9b3d15f13ae11f882126b026c -->', NULL, 'Media', 'The Guardian', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:36'),
(502, 4, 'guard_3ee121ed95212ef11466c756c6ee8c51', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2011/oct/16/vat-rules-raise-cosmetic-surgery-cost', 'Facelift and breast enlargement bills to rise under new VAT guidelines', 'Press Association', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/10/16/1318790167426/vat-added-to-cosmetic-sur-003.jpg', '2011-10-16 20:38:40', NULL, 'Plastic surgeons say patients will have to pay 20% more for cosmetic operations under new rules', '<!-- Redistribution rights for this field are unavailable -->', NULL, 'UK news', 'The Guardian', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:36'),
(503, 4, 'guard_8763a152e84e0ac2c243b8b68110ff8c', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2011/oct/16/manchester-weekender-offers-madcap-tour', 'Manchester Weekender offers madcap tour into city''s heritage', 'Dave Simpson', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pixies/2011/10/16/1318790454656/Helen-Storey-dresses-003.jpg', '2011-10-16 20:42:07', NULL, 'Three days of cultural celebration include over 70 events ranging from Jarvis Cocker''s tales, to a vegetable orchestra', '<p>It''s Saturday morning in Manchester''s Piccadilly Gardens, and an elderly shopper is gazing intently into Debenhams'' window at a silver mannequin covered in a white shawl. She doesn''t seem particularly excited to hear that this is part of fashion designer Helen Storey''s "<a href="http://www.primitive-streak.org/" title="">provocative textile collection</a> telling the story of human life in stunning detail", or that it took 105 hours to embroider, or is called (ahem) the sperm dress. "It looks like my net curtains," she decides, before fleeing towards soft furnishings.</p><p>The rude net curtains – sorry, concept piece about reproduction – formed just one of the delights of the <a href="http://www.creativetourist.com/the-manchester-weekender-2011" title="">Manchester Weekender 2011</a>. The three days of "constant cultural celebration" include over 70 events ranging from Jarvis Cocker packing the town hall with tales of being a "cultural provocateur" to a symphony orchestra whose instruments are vegetables. I start with the Floating Family Day Out, which offered a "taste of modern history" via a barge.</p><p>Alas, it turns out that not only is there a boat race on at the same time, but two of the racers have crashed into each other, creating the Manchester Ship Canal equivalent of a motorway pile-up.</p><p>"There''s going to be a delay," admits one of the happy, yellow T-shirted Weekender staffers, pointing us towards the nearby <a href="[http://www.creativetourist.com/the-manchester-weekender-2011" title="">People''s Museum</a>[http://www.phm.org.uk/]  and its century-old political world of collusion between Tories and Liberals, struggles for democracy and abuse of power (phew, thank cripes it''s not like that anymore).</p><p>An hour later, we''re still marooned on a motionless vessel, full of kids contending with instructions to make a little paper boat and misbehaving adults making paper jets. "At least we can still see the pub," says one, encouragingly, before the boat eventually chugs past the mist over the soapworks and yer actual graffiti artists in action.</p><p>It''s similarly farcical but rewarding at the Manchester Football Tour when just two of us turn up. "I''m not sure 3pm on a Saturday afternoon is the best time to do this," sighs tour guide Ed Glinert, rueing the 50,000 potential customers watching Manchester City up the road. Nevertheless, the author of the <a href="http://www.newmanchesterwalks.com/about/" title="">Manchester Compendium</a> knows his stuff, and thrills his tiny rapt audience with sights such as the building where the Football League was formed and nightclub where "Bestie" was <a href="http://www.mdmarchive.co.uk/archive/showartefact.php?vid=729" title="">arrested</a>. We''re spared "the exact rubbish bin where Wayne Rooney urinated outside the Panacea nightclub" but it''s impossible not to be enthralled by weird historical tales like the one about how a goalkeeper''s escaping dog led to Newton Heath FC becoming Manchester United – the businessman who returned the animal went on to buy the struggling club, meaning the world''s biggest football club owe it all to a lively St Bernard.)</p><p>A madcap day ends on the Bridgewater Hall tour, which reveals the eyebrow-raising secrets behind the premier classical venue''s <a href="http://www.bridgewater-hall.co.uk/content/YourVisit/Guidedtours.aspx" title="">pin-drop-in-row-Z acoustics</a>, including how the entire venue is mounted on 150 huge springs to stop vibration from passing trams. "They''re like bedsprings, but more so," explains fount-of-knowledge tour guide Richard, within the vast, spooky foundations.</p><p>I''ve clocked up a small fortune in parking fees and missed Jarvis Cocker, but have learned something about Manchester''s rich cultural heritage that lurks, taken for granted, all around us. And anyway, I don''t think Pulp''s singer would have told me how to make a little paper boat.</p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/uk&k=Manchester&k=UK+news&k=Heritage&k=Culture" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/uk/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/uk/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=Manchester+Weekender+offers+madcap+tour+into+city%27s+heritage+Article+1648445&ch=UK+news&c2=60753&c4=Manchester%2CUK+news%2CHeritage+%28Culture%29%2CCulture&c3=The+Guardian&c6=Dave+Simpson&c7=11-Oct-16&c8=1648445&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: uk/2011/oct/16/manchester-weekender-offers-madcap-tour|2011-10-16T21:13:33+01:00|1ad9c0c6c328baeda5089d6203e8899124b5d68d -->', NULL, 'UK news', 'The Guardian', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:36'),
