(506, 4, 'guard_a1e7a2256701f8acee901197684991ba', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/2011/oct/16/voices-tottenham-marginalised', 'The voices of Tottenham are being marginalised | Stafford Scott', 'Stafford Scott', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/10/16/1318782720931/The-Tottenham-riots-Augus-003.jpg', '2011-10-16 20:50:01', NULL, '<strong>Stafford Scott:</strong> Slogans and stickers will not help the area recover. Calls for justice must be heard – otherwise we''ll see a repeat of the riots', '<p>Along Tottenham High Road you cannot help but notice the "I Love Tottenham" stickers emblazoned on every lamppost and in nearly every shop. This is a local-authority-conceived campaign, one that it hopes will bolster community, consumer and investor confidence in the area. As someone who genuinely does love Tottenham I do not wish to undermine the initiative, but it''s impossible not to question the goals of the campaign when the logo gives no insight into why I, or anyone else, should believe in this particular area.</p><p>What does "I love Tottenham" mean to those people who took part in the events of 7 August, which followed the shooting of Mark Duggan by the police? Do they love Tottenham? Well they might do, if you can love somewhere and hate it at the same time.</p><p>For most of those I know who took part, Tottenham is the only home they''ve ever had; some of them have never strayed far from its borders. Far too many have never been outside London. For them it''s where they feel most at ease. But for many it is also a prison. They were born on Tottenham''s estates, and see little chance of escaping. These estates can be desperate places to live.</p><p>I doubt that the "I Love Tottenham" merchandise will make its way on to the estates in any meaningful way. For the residents know this is yet another cosmetic exercise, similar to the spending of £30m on the <a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/theguardian/from-the-archive-blog/2011/aug/08/anger-tottenham-broadwater-riots-1985" title="The Guardian - From the Archive Blog: Anger smoulders in Tottenham: the Broadwater Farm riots of 1985">Broadwater Farm estate</a> in the 1990s. It''s designed to make those who are passing through think that change has occurred when really nothing could be further from the truth. Haringey council and Tottenham''s MP David Lammy have done some good work supporting those who have lost their homes and businesses: for this they should be applauded. But they have shied away from engaging with those whose actions placed Tottenham in the media spotlight once again.</p><p>It''s a reminder of how different it all was in 1985, when <a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/2000/apr/10/guardianobituaries.obituaries" title="The Guardian - Bernie Grant obituary">Bernie Grant</a> was the leader of Haringey council. Instead of giving the kneejerk reactions we have seen from today''s politicians, he sought to provide a different perspective: he spoke to us before speaking to the media, but most importantly he didn''t say one thing off camera and another thing on camera. That''s why there were no more riots in Tottenham – even after the killings of <a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2007/mar/09/ukcrime.gender" title="The Guardian - When the police got it wrong">Joy Gardner in 1993</a> and <a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/education/2003/oct/22/highereducation.race" title="The Guardian - Our role in racial equality">Roger Sylvester in 1999</a> – while Grant was our MP. There was a feeling that someone in authority cared and would represent their views. Those I speak with today feel no one is remotely interested in hearing their stories, much less willing to represent them.</p><p>Those who are able to speak about the real reasons Tottenham was set ablaze are now finding themselves ignored by the local authority. One well-known reverend, who used to virtually eat, drink and sleep with the council, is no longer invited into the same room after he had the temerity to state publicly that he believed an injustice was being done. The local authority should be listening to him: he has had a glimpse into the lives of those blighted by their policies.</p><p>These actions only add to the sense of isolation and marginalisation that some in Tottenham''s black community have endured for decades. It seems that these politicians have learned little from the expensive public inquiries that they paid for, such as <a href="http://oro.open.ac.uk/4545/" title="Journal of Social Policy - The Scarman Report, the Macpherson Report and the Media: how newspapers respond to race-centred social policy interventions ">Scarman, Gifford and Macpherson</a>.</p><p>Lammy has told me that Grant''s stance saw Tottenham ostracised by the politicians; but Tottenham had been forgotten long before Bernie became our MP. While he may not have brought the ministerial visits we have seen recently, Lammy shouldn''t think he himself brought them here either: the riots did. And Grant brought us something much more profound than ministers: he brought us hope, gave us pride, and provided us with leadership.</p><p>Martin Luther King once said that riots gave a voice to the voiceless; but the voices of those who felt moved to take to the streets in August are still very much unheard. The lessons from the 80s should tell us that ignoring them will come at a cost.</p><p>These people are the "already marginalised", or the offspring of the "already marginalised": the ones who were excluded from school in disproportionate numbers; who were arrested and convicted under "<a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sus_law" title="Wikipedia - Sus laws">sus</a>" laws in disproportionate numbers; who are being stopped and searched in disproportionate numbers. They see themselves as victims too: to further marginalise them will only make them feel squeezed between a rock and an even harder place. As far as they are concerned, they are being left with no alternative but to lash out. So telling them that sentences are going to increase is akin to telling someone strapped with a bomb, "Stop or I''ll shoot!"</p><p>I love Tottenham, but it''s the people that make it lovable, not slogans. It will need much more than a sticker campaign if we are to ensure that none of this plays out on our streets again.</p><p>Equality, fairness and justice must be on the table, for without this the regeneration of Tottenham High Road will be meaningless to many of its inhabitants, and the likelihood of another riot erupting will remain a distinct possibility.</p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/commentisfree&k=UK+riots&k=Race+issues&k=London&k=Tottenham&k=Mark+Duggan&k=UK+news" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/commentisfree/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/commentisfree/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=The+voices+of+Tottenham+are+being+marginalised+%7C+Stafford+Scott+Article+1648402&ch=Comment+is+free&c2=60753&c4=UK+riots%2CRace+issues+%28News%29%2CLondon+%28News%29%2CTottenham+News+tag+%28area+of+London%29%2CMark+Duggan%2CUK+news%2CSociety&c3=The+Guardian&c6=Stafford+Scott&c7=11-Oct-16&c8=1648402&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: commentisfree/2011/oct/16/voices-tottenham-marginalised|2011-10-16T21:13:35+01:00|6d2be545a92aa961b63f1c71a1313edbea91f93f -->', NULL, 'Comment is free', 'The Guardian', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:39'),
(507, 4, 'guard_e4ef678bfc07b3e9b5e0abf0568f489f', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2011/oct/15/strictly-come-dancing-live', 'Strictly Come Dancing: liveblog!', 'Heidi Stephens', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/10/14/1318604889386/Strictly-Come-Dancing-003.jpg', '2011-10-16 20:58:00', NULL, '<p><strong>Heidi Stephens:</strong> Who will go this week? Join me from 6.25pm on Saturday as the celebrities try to avoid the chop</p>', '<!-- Block 1 --><p>Good evening, and welcome to our Strictly Come Dancing Liveblog! It''s Broadway week!  I THINK this means that Dave Arch and his orchestra will be leaving David Guetta well alone for a week and putting their ear-bleeding spin on Broadway classics instead.  I guess we can also expect some gratuitous raiding of the props cupboard, and dancing/costumes with a more theatrical flavour.  What joy.  </p><p>It''s probably worth mentioning at this point that I loathe musicals with every fibre in my being, along with lyrical interpretation and fannying about with props and mime and all that jazz.  But this is Strictly, and as @Sharkwald said on Twitter "I''m expecting more camp than a remake of Carry On Camping featuring John Barrowman and Graham Norton".  So put on your legwarmers, form a chorus line and get into the spirit of the occasion *big grin, jazz hands*.</p><p>The GOOD news for this evening is there''s more variation on the dancing – we''ve got the full mix of waltzes, latin, quickstep, foxtrot and tango, which makes it all a bit more interesting.  AND the departure of Edwina last week means the show is ten minutes shorter, so we can finally be grateful to her for something.  </p><p>I''ll be here from 6.25pm to document every tassel, twirl and trodden toe – do join me in the comment box with your thoughts and opinions – they are invariably the best bit.</p><p>See you later!</p><!-- Block 2 --><p><span class="timestamp">6.19pm:</span> Just watching the end of Celebrity Masterchef.  Who are all these people?  I don''t recognise any of them.  Clearly I need to watch more TV.</p><p>Ooh, it''s nearly time!  *gets tea and snacks, prepares for interminable dance/liveblog marathon*</p><!-- Block 3 --><p><span class="timestamp">6.26pm:</span> And we''re OFF.  Apparently The Fonz is on the red button giving his opinions.  Why aren''t we liveblogging THAT?</p><p>Last week - a mixed bag of dancing and horrid dresses.  Edwina left.  Fin.  Tonight it''s Broadway week, and we should hail a yellow cab.  Can we get a taxi for Sir Bruce?</p><!-- Block 4 --><p><span class="timestamp">6.28pm:</span> The pro dancers are doing their opening dance thing, to a song that I THINK is from A Chorus Line (please don''t give me a hard time about this, I really haven''t a clue).</p><p>On the subject of which - just for my own sanity and to give some semblance that I know what I''m doing, I have made a note of which Broadway musical each couple''s chosen tracks come from – blogging non-stop for two hours is hard enough without wondering what the infernal racket is.</p><p>Ooh, the celebrities have turned up in the opening dance!  That was ill-advised, it''s all gone a bit shambolic.</p><!-- Block 5 --><p><span class="timestamp">6.31pm:</span> Here come Sir Bruce and Tess!  Tess''s dress has a horrible pair of lace knickers sewn into the front, and something appears to be nesting in her hair.  She is promising us razzle, and also dazzle.  I''ll just take the dazzle, thanks.</p><!-- Block 6 --><p><span class="timestamp">6.33pm:</span> Here come the celebs - eyes peeled for horrid frocks!  Chelsee''s obsession with fringe continues, whereas Holly appears to be wearing bondage gear and Anita has been at the dressing up box.  AGAIN.</p><!-- Block 7 --><p><span class="timestamp">6.36pm:</span> First up it''s <strong>Holly and Artem</strong>!  They are dancing the tango to ''Cell Block Tango'' from Chicago.  This is a musical I have actually seen! </p><p>Out they come - Holly is in a jail cell looking like Elvira Mistress of the Dark.  Loving her black wig though.  </p><p>Her tango is big on character, but still a bit spongy - she can certainly dance, but it''s all a bit...floppy, somehow.  It was all fine until she got out of the cage.  Also Holly and Artem have no chemistry at ALL, something that was very apparent from the start with Kara and Artem last year.  I also wish he''d stop wearing mesh vests.</p><!-- Block 8 --><p><span class="timestamp">6.39pm:</span> What do the judges thing of Holly and Artem''s tango?  Len thought is was full of smolder, and he loved it.  Alesha though it lacked intensity, but she got Bruno going.  Craig liked the storytelling, but her tango needed to be cleaner and sharper.  I concur.</p><p>Scores - 7 from Craig, 8 from Len, 7 from Alesha and 8 from Bruno - a total of 30.  Great start for Holly and Artem, only 12 couples to go!</p><!-- Block 9 --><p><span class="timestamp">6.44pm:</span> Next up is <strong>Dan and Katya</strong>!</p><p>This week they are dancing the Viennese waltz, inexplicably to Queen''s ''Somebody To Love'' from We Will Rock You.  OK, we''ll go with it, but it better not spoil the Viennese waltz, it''s my favourite.   </p><p>Out they come - Dan wearing a horrible leather waistcoat, and Katya managing to rock electric blue in a way that Edwina entirely failed to do last week.</p><p>Oh Dan, Dan.  You know I adore you.  But you look like the coat hanger is still jammed in your shirt, and your teeth are gritted.  It''s just not very...romantic, is it?</p><!-- Block 10 --><p><span class="timestamp">6.48pm:</span> Judges'' verdict - needs a bit more fluidity, and he didn''t really capture the magic and intensity of the song.  Craig though he was awkward, and by the end he didn''t have a neck.  That''ll be the coat hanger.  Len thought it was difficult because Dan is tall.  Lots of men are tall, Len.  It''s the nature of men.</p><p>Scores - 5 from Craig, 7 from Len, 6 from Alesha and 6 from Bruno - total of 24 for Dan and Katya.</p><!-- Block 11 --><p><span class="timestamp">6.52pm:</span> Next up is <strong>Anita and Robin!</strong>.  They are dancing the Jive  to ''You Can''t Stop The Beat'' from Hairspray.  I have never seen Hairspray.  It looks awful.</p><p>Out they come.  Anita is dressed like a pink doll, the sort that wee on demand and cry when you turn them upside down.  Alas, neither of these things happen.  There are props, and pinkness, and stompy jiving, and Anita grinning maniacally.  Never mind the beat, wish someone would stop Anita Dobson.  I suspect heavy machinery couldn''t stop her.</p><!-- Block 12 --><p><span class="timestamp">6.56pm:</span> Judges verdict - not precise enough, too loose and messy, but according to Len "fun, energetic and entertaining".  Yes, and so are CLOWNS.  And they are still SCARY.</p><p>Scores time!  6 from Craig, 7 from Len, 7 from Alesha and 7 from Bruno - total of 27 for Anita and Robin.</p><!-- Block 13 --><p><span class="timestamp">6.58pm:</span> Are we there yet?  Ah, apparently not.  Another ten to go.  Next up is <strong>Alex and James!</strong> They are dancing a Viennese Waltz  to ''Memory'' from the musical Cats.  </p><p>Neither of them is dressed in a cat costume, disappointingly, although someone in the orchestra is wailing like a kitten stuck in a tumble dryer.  Alex''s dress is mostly lilac netting, and she has Elaine Paige''s hair.</p><p>Oh, this is MUCH more like it.  It''s all proper romantic and floaty, as a Viennese Waltz should be.  I don''t care what the judges say, I LOVED that.  More please.</p><!-- Block 14 --><p><span class="timestamp">7.03pm:</span> Craig loved it, although he would have liked it to have been a little more daring.  Len thought it was beautiful, and Bruno bangs on about birds taking flight.  I think he likes it.  Hard to know with Bruno sometimes.  He''s a giant complex metaphor.</p><p>Scores - eights all round, a total of 32.  Great dance from Alex, this evening is LOOKING UP.</p><!-- Block 15 --><p><span class="timestamp">7.06pm:</span> Right, I''m all warmed up now.  Who''s next?  It''s It''s <strong>Rory and Erin</strong>!  Tonight they are dancing the Quickstep to ''Top Hat, White Tie and Tails'' from Top Hat.  </p><p>Rory has the tails, the top hat and the cane - so many things to trip over. Erin is wearing a Christmas fairy light curtain attached to a dead swan.</p><p>Rory is actually very good - from where I''m sitting, his footwork looks excellent, albeit his top half looks a bit stiff.  Or maybe it''s supposed to be like that?</p><p>Well, I rather enjoyed that.</p><!-- Block 16 --><p><span class="timestamp">7.10pm:</span> Len loved it - Rory''s best dance so far.  Lots of razzle and dazzle, and Rory held his character to the end.  Which of course is what Rory does.  Craig thought his hands were flat and his posture wasn''t great, but full of panache nonetheless.</p><p>"Here comes the quickstepper" says Tess, clearly trying to be down with the kidz.  The kidz aren''t watching, Tess, but I''m with you. </p><p>7 from Craig, and 8s from the others - a total of 31.</p><!-- Block 17 --><p><span class="timestamp">7.13pm:</span> Next up is <strong>Lulu and Brendan</strong>!  Tonight they are dancing the Rumba to ''All I Ask Of You'' from Phantom of the Opera.  All Brendan asks of Lulu is that she follows the steps, and doesn''t fall over.  It shouldn''t be too much to ask, should it?</p><p>In training, Lulu is crying, because she isn''t elegant and can''t do it.  To help her, Brendan makes her wear an Andrew Lloyd-Webber mask.  Yes, that''ll do it.</p><p>Lulu is wearing a Halloween costume, but somehow makes it look good.  Brendan is flapping a cape about, and mouthing the words.   The singing is awful, but the dancing is all quite...sensual, which in the context of Lulu and Brendan is all a bit disturbing.  But isn''t the rumba a latin dance? Why are they wafting about to Phantom? I''m confused.  Also, I know nothing.</p><!-- Block 18 --><p><span class="timestamp">7.17pm:</span> Judges verdict - a good effort from Lulu, who is improving every week.  But Brendan put in an illegal lift and Craig plans to penalise him for it.  Handbags at dawn!</p><p>Scores are in - 5 from Craig and 7s from the others - a total of 26.</p><!-- Block 19 --><p><span class="timestamp">7.21pm:</span> Next up it''s <strong>Nancy and Anton!</strong> They are dancing the Tango  to ''Be Italian'' from Nine.  This is a musical I have never heard of.  </p><p>Out they come - Nancy looks every inch the flamenco vixen in a scarlet toilet brush.  Clearly she is trying to compensate for her lack of dancing ability by sitting on a chair and flashing her legs.  She also looks a bit drunk, if I''m honest.  GO Nancy.</p><p>Now, as tangos go, this looks alright to me, but what do I know.  Clearly this is much more Nancy''s cup of tea, albeit a spiked cup.  I mean she''s still rubbish and her feet and arms are all over the shop, but it''s better.</p><!-- Block 20 --><p><span class="timestamp">7.25pm:</span> Nancy and Bruce do a horrible routine about her being invited to Bruce''s dressing room.  A nation cringes.  Anton looks like he''s had enough.</p><p>Bruno enjoyed it, but Craig thought she was a "plodding mule".  Ooh, harsh. Len thought there was lots of style, but no substance.  </p><p>Scores for Nancy - 4 from Craig, 5 from Len, 5 from Alesha and 6 from Bruno - a total of 20.</p><!-- Block 21 --><p><span class="timestamp">7.29pm:</span> Who''s next?  It''s Audley and Natalie!  He has size 17 feet, in case you didn''t know.  They are dancing the Samba  to ''Too Darn Hot'' from Kiss Me Kate.  They do their training in a Bikram yoga studio.  It''s hot, see?  Nope, me neither.</p><p>Out they come - Audley is dressed like a professional snooker player, and Natalie is dressed like a belly dancer.  Is this what Kiss Me Kate is about?</p><p>It''s all a bit...shuffly, and he keeps tripping over his own feet.  Audley''s doing his best, bless him, but dancefloor hotness is not something he has in excess.</p><!-- Block 22 --><p><span class="timestamp">7.33pm:</span> Craig though Audley''s timing was out, but Audley was lighter of foot than he expected.  However his feet still need work, and he needs more spring in his step.</p><p>Oh god, are they going to talk about how big Audley''s feet are until Christmas?  It''s only week 2, it''s getting boring now.</p><p>Scores - 5 from Craig, 6 from Len and Alesha, and 7 from Bruno - total of 24.</p><!-- Block 23 --><p><span class="timestamp">7.35pm:</span> I think there are only 5 left - stick with me!  Next up it''s <strong>Robbie and Ola</strong>!  They are dancing the Tango to ''Gimme, Gimme, Gimme'' from Mama Mia.  I''m sure the Broadway purists are grinding their teeth at the choice of such populist numbers, but I suspect this may be for philistines like me.  I''ve seen the film, does that count?  </p><p>Robbie has greased his hair back, and has got his guns out.  His tango intensity stare is horrible, as is his tango. He bum is sticking out in a most unpleasant manner, making him tango like a chicken.</p><p>I can also report that Dave Arch''s orchestra is singing this song marginally less competently than Meryl Streep.  Or was it Julie Walters?  I forget.</p><!-- Block 24 --><p><span class="timestamp">7.39pm:</span> Len thought it was full of attack and aggression, and a good effort.  Alesha loved it - really?  Bruno just needs to stop, it''s giving me a headache.  Even Craig liked it.  Was I watching something else?  Or is the tango supposed to look like that?</p><p>Scores - 7s from Craig and Len, 8s from Alesha and Bruno - a total of 30.</p><!-- Block 25 --><p><span class="timestamp">7.42pm:</span> It''s time for <strong>Russell and Flavia</strong>!  They are dancing the Foxtrot to ''Rain On My Parade'' from Funny Girl.  </p><p>Russell gives the distinct impression of someone who has found his spiritual home – forget all that astrology rubbish, he''s all about the ballroom.   I have to say it makes him far more appealing than when he was wearing terrible knitwear and babbling on about the moon being in Jupiter.  </p><p>Tonight he is wearing white tails and a white top hat, which makes him look like Willy Wonka, whereas Flavia''s yellow dress and tan combination make her look like a banana on the turn.  Russell is splendidly light of foot and doing a very decent foxtrot.  He''s clearly having a ball, is great to watch, and I love him.</p><!-- Block 26 --><p><span class="timestamp">7.47pm:</span> The judges loved it, apart from Craig who would have preferred a more "masculine approach".  Hahaha.  Pot, have you met kettle?</p><p>Scores - 6 from Craig, 7 from Len, 7 from Alesha and 8 from Bruno - a total of 28.</p><!-- Block 27 --><p><span class="timestamp">7.50pm:</span> Well, that was fun.  Now it''s time for <strong>Jason and Kristina!</strong>  They are dancing the Tango to ''I Will Survive'' from Priscilla Queen of the Desert – familiar territory for Ja-Do, who has starred in this in the West End.  Can he do a manly tango?</p><p>Also, does Kristina own any dresses that cover her torso?  This one is so pink it hurts.  It''s also the most un-butch tango I''ve ever seen - he might has well have done it in a rainbow cape and heels.  His footwork is excellent, but suddenly it''s goes all disco.  I DON''T UNDERSTAND.</p><p>Also, tango-ing to Gloria Gaynor should be BANNED FOR ALL ETERNITY.</p><!-- Block 28 --><p><span class="timestamp">7.54pm:</span> The judges loved the manly/camp/manly combo.  Oh, I have no idea what to think any more.</p><p>Scores - 9s all round - an impressive 36 for Jason, who is rapidly lining up to be the favourite in this competition.</p><!-- Block 29 --><p><span class="timestamp">7.56pm:</span> THERE ARE ONLY TWO LEFT!  YAY!  Don''t turn over to X Factor, nothing happens for the first 15 minutes anyway.</p><p>Next up it''s <strong>Chelsee and Pasha!</strong> They are dancing the Cha Cha to ''Beggin'' from Jersey Boys.   The singing is an all-time low, and Chelsee''s hair seems to get bigger by the week.   I''m beggin'' her to put an outfit on that doesn''t involve fringing. </p><p>Chelsee''s cha cha looks great - really sharp footwork and she''s clearly having a ball. LOVED THAT.</p><!-- Block 30 --><p><span class="timestamp">8.00pm:</span> Craig thought she had great timing and energy, but it was haphazard and a bit disco.  She needs more precision, but she''s got loads of potential.  I really enjoy watching her dance, at least she''s never boring.</p><p>Scores - 6 from Craig, 8 from Len, 8 from Alesha and 8 from Bruno - a very solid 30 for Chelsee.</p><!-- Block 31 --><p><span class="timestamp">8.03pm:</span> Last, but definitely not least, it''s It''s <strong>Harry and Aliona!</strong> They are dancing the jive to ''Grease Lightning'' from Grease – another musical I have actually seen in its stage form.  The only thing I remember is going to the ladies during the interval and inadvertently smacking actress Jane Seymour in the face with a door.</p><p>Anyway, Harry''s chest is out.  That is all you need to know, costume-wise.  His jiving is also pretty decent too, but that''s almost by the by.  My only issue is that there seemed to be very little actual jiving.</p><!-- Block 32 --><p><span class="timestamp">8.07pm:</span> The judges enjoyed it, but would have liked less messing about.  Me too.  Bruno is perving and I wish he''d stop.  Craig is too, but is at least more subtle about it.</p><p>Scores for Harry and his lovely chest - 8 from Craig, 8 from Len, 9 from Alesha and 8 from Bruno - a total of 33.</p><!-- Block 33 --><p><span class="timestamp">8.10pm:</span> So that''s it for tonight - Jason is at the top for the third week in a row, with Nancy at the bottom.  I hope she goes this week, the theatricals are getting on my nerves and I fear for Anton''s sanity.  </p><p>Thanks for all your comments once again - I''ll be back here tomorrow for the results show at 7.25, so join me then to find out who''s leaving the dancefloor for good!  See you then!</p><!-- Block 34 --><p><strong>*RESULTS SHOW UPDATE!*</strong></p><p>It''s time to find out who''s going home!  It''s only half an hour, hang on in there.  Then you can pop over to the other side for X Factor.  Stu Heritage is also doing a brilliant liveblog.</p><p>The pros are dancing to "America" from West Side Story.  This is a musical I know!  My dad had the album and played it to death throughout my childhood.</p><!-- Block 35 --><p><span class="timestamp">7.28pm:</span> See, all the girls have got nice, sensible, body-covering outfits on, and they look fabulous.  Why do we have to be subjected to such horrors on a Saturday night?</p><p>Talking of horrors, Tess is wearing a cream one-shouldered dress adorned with cheap-looking sparkly rubbish.  How has her stylist not been fired?  Claudia is channelling Mystic Meg.  Perhaps she''s going into business with Russell.</p><p>Ah, the interminable recap of last night *goes to make tea*.</p><!-- Block 36 --><p><span class="timestamp">7.34pm:</span> So who''s staying and who''s going?  Well Audley''s definitely not in the bottom two, which I think is good news.</p><p>First person in the bottom two - Dan and Katya!  The lovely Dan Lobb!  How can it be?</p><!-- Block 37 --><p><span class="timestamp">7.38pm:</span> The stars of the new Footloose movie have jetted in to perform.  I remember the original film with the fondness of youth.  I''m sure if I watched it now it would be terrible.</p><p>Mostly male dancer is throwing female dancer about like a beanbag.  He''s no Kevin Bacon, is he?  Oh, thank god.  It''s all livened up a bit.</p><!-- Block 38 --><p><span class="timestamp">7.42pm:</span> What IS Claudia wearing?  It appears to be a black poncho/cape affair.  Is her entire wardrobe Halloween costumes? </p><p>Brace yourself for Len''s Lens.  It may be pointless filler, but at least it''s alliterative.</p><!-- Block 39 --><p><span class="timestamp">7.47pm:</span> Right, time to find out who''s the other person in the bottom two.  Has Tess been borrowing lipstick off 2 Shoes?</p><p>Ooh, Lulu''s not in the bottom two!  Which sort of rhymes.</p><p>It''s Nancy!  She''s in the bottom two with Dan.  Of course it should be Dan that stays, when do they start doing the dance-off thing?</p><!-- Block 40 --><p><span class="timestamp">7.51pm:</span> Just when you thought this show couldn''t get any more tedious, it''s Susan Boyle singing Unchained Melody.  I never thought the day would come when I''d long for Robson &amp; Jerome.</p><p>Susan is hungering for someone''s touch.  Let''s consider that for a while.</p><!-- Block 41 --><p><span class="timestamp">7.54pm:</span> Nancy would be sad to leave.  Anton is trying to look sad, but I suspect that inside he''s singing the Hallelujah Chorus.</p><p>So who''s leaving?  *crosses fingers for Nancy* - it''s <strong>DAN AND KATYA!</strong> This makes me sad.  I can only assume that the nation has decided to punish him for that leather waistcoat.</p><!-- Block 42 --><p><span class="timestamp">7.58pm:</span> So that''s another week of Strictly over – two contestants down, 12 to go (eek!).  Thanks again for joining in with all your comments – I''ll be back here next week for some more dancefloor action.  In the meantime you can follow me on Twitter @heidistephens.  See you next week! Hx</p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/tv-and-radio&k=Strictly+Come+Dancing&k=Television&k=Reality+TV" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/tv-and-radio/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/tv-and-radio/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=Strictly+Come+Dancing%3A+liveblog%21+Article+1647908&ch=Television+%26amp%3B+radio&c2=60753&c4=Strictly+Come+Dancing%2CTelevision+%28Culture%29%2CReality+TV+%28TV+genre%29&c3=guardian.co.uk&c6=Heidi+Stephens&c7=11-Oct-16&c8=1647908&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: tv-and-radio/tvandradioblog/2011/oct/15/strictly-come-dancing-live|2011-10-16T21:13:35+01:00|2c8dfb213a3a95a1111b95ae51a5959821b23849 -->', NULL, 'Television &amp; radio', 'guardian.co.uk', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:39'),
(508, 4, 'guard_b0d9caed7fc8dddf85eaf6df7ff59d97', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/2011/oct/16/uniqlo-signed-susan-sarandon-triumph', 'That Uniqlo has signed Susan Sarandon should be seen as a triumph for older women. There''s just one problem …', 'Hadley Freeman', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2011/10/14/1318594277922/Susan-Sarandon-003.jpg', '2011-10-16 20:59:01', NULL, 'She is a fine actor and possibly one of the sexiest women ever born, but I just cannot bear her', '<p><strong>I have noticed that Demi Moore, Julianne Moore and Susan Sarandon are the faces of various high-street fashion chains this season. Does that&nbsp;mean retailers are now paying attention to older women?</strong></p><p><em>Sharon, New York</em></p><p></p><p>It would be nice to think that, wouldn''t it? And who knows, maybe they are, or at least maybe they are finally realising that older women tend to have more money than the anorexic Russian teenagers to whom they usually seem to be trying to appeal, judging from the women they use in their adverts. True, the fact that Demi has admitted to having had plastic surgery somewhat undermines the idea that the fashion industry is developing healthier ideas of how women look, but no matter.</p><p>So well done to American retailers <a href="http://fashion.elle.com/fashion/2011/08/02/julianne-demis-fall-campaign-face-off/" title="">Ann Taylor and Talbots for hiring Demi Moore and Julianne Moore</a>, although maybe they just hired them for their last name as opposed to their maturity and beauty. Apparently, there is a huge untapped market out there for women whose surname is "Moore".</p><p>Now, if I were a true professional I&nbsp;would see <a href="http://www.wwd.com/media-news/fashion-memopad/susan-sarandon-one-of-many-in-uniqlos-fall-campaign-5108517?src=rss/recentstories/20110906" title="">Uniqlo''s signing of Susan Sarandon</a> as even more of a triumph. Talbots does aim at a somewhat older market, so for it to use older models, while commendable, is not actually that mould-breaking. Uniqlo, however, aims primarily, if not solely, at a younger generation, so using 64-year-old Sarandon in its adverts really is an impressive step. Or it would be, were I&nbsp;a professional.</p><p>You see, to be a true professional journalist, one should tuck one''s emotions away and merely report on the story itself. Facts, dear boy, facts, and all that. But I''m afraid I ... cannot ... hold … in … any … more! My God, I just cannot <em>bear</em> Sarandon.</p><p>She is a very fine actor and quite possibly one of the sexiest women ever born, and yet instead of cheering on this sexy sixtysomething, whenever I&nbsp;see her step up to a podium to give an award to someone, I just want to claw my own ears off my head. Like Sean Penn and Helen Hunt, Sarandon has always come across as so spectacularly humourless, sanctimonious and lacking in self-awareness that no matter how I try to like her, I end up scratching away at my lobes.</p><p>I used to feel guilty about this. After all, irrational hatred of celebrities one has never even met is surely one of the great ills of the modern day, along with internet-induced ADD and flavoured coffees. But then, about two years ago, I happened to see Ms Sarandon walking up the red carpet to, if memory serves, the Oscars when she was stopped by the star of E! himself, Ryan Seacrest. At first, Sarandon did her usual shtick, solemnly lecturing E!''s audience about, if memory is still serving, the victims in Haiti, a very commendable thing to lecture on. When Seacrest then told her they didn''t have much time left, she hastily switched subjects to detailing where each part of her outfit had come from, taking special care to give a shout to her jewellers, banging on about her earrings for veritable yonks. Well, you gotta please the advertisers and fashion press offices, right? Oh, Sarandon. Go off and wrap yourself in some colourful knitwear and don''t hit your sexy butt on the way out, girlfriend.</p><p></p><p><strong>OK, so you established that </strong><a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/lifeandstyle/2011/oct/09/anna-wintour-kanye-west-vogue" title=""><strong>Anna  Wintour probably didn''t like Kanye West''s fashion line</strong></a><strong> last week – but what do you think?</strong></p><p><em>Marcus, by email</em></p><p></p><p>Again, I shall reveal my unprofessional nature. Kanye West wrote possibly <a href="http://youtu.be/qLnS-2h_nog" title="">the worst rhyme in modern music</a> – "Have you ever had sex with a pharaoh/Put the pussy in a sarcophagus/Now she claiming that I bruised her esophogus" – and <a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/commentisfree/cifamerica/2011/oct/12/kanye-west-occupy-wall-street" title="">I still love him</a>, so some bad clothes aren''t going to bother me too&nbsp;much.</p><p>In my Anchorman-obsessed mind, Kanye is the Steve Carell to Jay-Z''s Will Ferrell, the id to the world''s super ego. This is a man who just does and says exactly what he wants and when he wants, and then spends the next two years writing songs about how sorry he&nbsp;is.</p><p>Thus, West''s collection was a predictable mish-mash of designers he admires and overly sexy clothes that he probably saw on the web at 3am the night before. And in all honesty, I would not want it any other way. The man is a talented enough musician. It would be downright weird if he became the next Martin Margiela, too, because that would at least suggest he wasn''t actually designing the clothes himself. But one look at those bandage dresses and frankly bonkers shoes tells you, yup, this is definitely the work of West.</p><p></p><p><em>• Post your questions to Hadley Freeman, Ask Hadley, The Guardian, Kings Place, 90 York Way, London N1 9GU. Email </em><a href="mailto:ask.hadley@guardian.co.uk" title="ask.hadley@guardian.co.uk"><em>ask.hadley@guardian.co.uk</em></a></p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/lifeandstyle&k=Fashion&k=Life+and+style&k=Kanye+West&k=Music" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/lifeandstyle/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/lifeandstyle/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=That+Uniqlo+has+signed+Susan+Sarandon+should+be+seen+as+a+triumph+for+older+women.+There%27s+just+one+problem+%E2%80%A6+Article+1647776&ch=Life+and+style&c2=60753&c4=Fashion%2CLife+and+style%2CKanye+West%2CMusic&c3=The+Guardian&c6=Hadley+Freeman&c7=11-Oct-16&c8=1647776&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: lifeandstyle/2011/oct/16/uniqlo-signed-susan-sarandon-triumph|2011-10-16T21:13:35+01:00|20db8631af157ceccdb8a468a290366c70e6024e -->', NULL, 'Life and style', 'The Guardian', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:39'),
(509, 4, 'guard_8a0df3af32ac65e10497fc4b777ea7ce', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/stage/2011/oct/16/josie-long-guerilla-comedy-tour', 'On the road with Josie Long''s ''guerilla'' comedy tour', 'Dan Hancox', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2011/10/14/1318604627023/Tom-Parry-Aisha-Mirza-Jos-003.jpg', '2011-10-16 20:59:01', NULL, 'It''s chaotic, random and beset by problems ranging from stag beetles to strong winds. But how are the fans finding it?', '<p>''That was the most random thing I''ve ever seen," mutters one teenager to another as they slink off into the Bedford night. "Yeah – but it was funny though."</p><p>Tucked behind a secret doorway to the 13th-century Bedford Castle mound, a crowd of young Bedfordians are watching a guerrilla gig lit only by a  streetlamp. These teens have stumbled on <a href="http://www.alternativerealitytour.com/" title="">Josie Long''s  Alternative Reality tour</a>, featuring fellow comedians Tiernan Douieb, Simon Munnery and Nathaniel Tapley, writer Alan Moore and singer Grace Petrie.</p><p>Their chaotic method is to roll up in town, find a suitable venue where they''re unlikely to get arrested, <a href="http://twitter.com/josielong" title="">announce it on Twitter</a>, then walk around the town  centre telling people about it. "Our main tools are social media and shouting," Long explains.</p><p>Crowd numbers have varied from seven to 70, and the feeling on the bus is that it''s been a challenging but inspiring journey.</p><p>The Bedford gig is beset by stag beetles, church bell ringing practice and howling winds, but there''s a  magical atmosphere. Afterwards some of the crowd discuss whether they could put on more free shows. "It feels like it''s been unfashionable to be a socialist for so long," Marisa Straccia remarks. "It''s  great that Josie''s coming to places like Bedford and beating the drum, reassuring people that we''re still here, and angry."</p><p></p><p>More information:  <a href="http://www.alternativerealitytour.com" title="">alternativerealitytour.com</a></p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/stage&k=Josie+Long&k=Comedy" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/stage/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/stage/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=On+the+road+with+Josie+Long%27s+%27guerilla%27+comedy+tour+Article+1647831&ch=Stage&c2=60753&c4=Josie+Long+%28comedian%29%2CComedy+%28culture%29&c3=The+Guardian&c6=Dan+Hancox&c7=11-Oct-16&c8=1647831&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: stage/2011/oct/16/josie-long-guerilla-comedy-tour|2011-10-16T21:13:35+01:00|de81afa9f851a7423fcef94000fa3527c24717a4 -->', NULL, 'Stage', 'The Guardian', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:39'),
(510, 4, 'guard_7f4497c3412671ff4352c572065ac1f4', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/music/2011/oct/16/jarvis-cocker-mother-brother-lover', 'Jarvis Cocker: the secrets of Pulp''s songs', 'Jarvis Cocker', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/10/14/1318615446636/Jarvis-Cocker-003.jpg', '2011-10-16 20:59:02', NULL, '<p>An exclusive extract from a&nbsp;new book of selected lyrics reveals the blueprint for the band''s signature style of narrative pop</p>', '<!-- Redistribution rights for this field are unavailable -->', NULL, 'Music', 'The Guardian', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:39'),
(511, 4, 'guard_48bfb3d5b8a53b5eb5c4c2fc345dee95', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/culture/2011/oct/16/gary-balow-songwriting', 'Gary Barlow: the one-man songwriting factory', 'Peter Robinson', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/About/General/2011/10/14/1318611677230/Give-a-song-Gary-003.jpg', '2011-10-16 21:00:00', NULL, 'Where does the Take That star and X Factor judge find the time to knock out all his songs?', '<p>As a teenager, Gary Barlow imagined that writing <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=W9mYlBo8MDI" title="">a million love songs</a> was  the perfect expression of how boundless his love could be. In 2011 his compliment works less well – on  current evidence it would be about a  morning''s work.</p><p>Last week Matt  Cardle released a Barlow composition called <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=coCwyRhb_2A" title="">Run  For Your Life</a>. Next month  <a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/tv-and-radio/2011/jun/03/britains-got-talent-ronan-parke" title="">controversial Britain''s Got Talent mini-man Ronan Parke''s</a> album will also include a new Barlow tune (Stronger Than I), and Westlife''s next single, Lighthouse, is yet another new song from the Barlow catalogue. Impressive stuff, particularly as Take That''s last album is just 11 months old, and an extra eight-song bonus album came out in May. But there''s more: having helmed (and looked very serious in the video for) this year''s <a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IIwTcA60BkE" title="">Children in Need single</a>, Barlow will also give yet another <a href="http://www.mtv.co.uk/news/the-x-factor/333412-the-x-factor-gary-barlow-winners-song" title="">brand new song</a> to the next X Factor winner.</p><p>"How does he do it?" is a fair question and, based on that Matt Cardle single, "by not always  exercising  rigorous quality control" seems like a suitable answer. It''s certainly true that the quality of the songs he has donated to those less fortunate has varied in quality almost as wildly as that of the artists themselves. (In recent years he has also provided songs for, among others, John Barrowman and Peter Kay''s comedy creation Geraldine McQueen.)</p><p>Perhaps during his wilderness years Barlow behaved <a href="http://www.google.com/hostednews/ukpress/article/ALeqM5hKHEbznw3NPseKUZkbkfExliR85Q?docId=N0839291318144378765A" title="">as if nothing was wrong</a>, like the sacked stockbroker who leaves for work each morning then spends his day on a park bench next to an empty briefcase. The idea of Barlow diligently penning an album''s worth of new material in time for non-release every Christmas for eight years would certainly explain the song mountain being slowly dismantled in 2011.</p><p>But the crucial point was  Simon Cowell deciding, with the arrival of X Factor USA, to go on holiday and leave Barlow not just babysitting Louis Walsh, but with the keys to the pop kingdom. To most pop stars this would signify party time. Gary "sensibleface" Barlow, remembering those years spent reading Take a Break on the park bench, knew this was his chance to make himself indispensable, and cast himself as the "Simon Cowell it''s OK to like", even though he''s still a <a href="http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/election-2010/7597261/General-Election-2010-Gary-Barlow-unveiled-as-David-Cameron-backer.html" title="">very big Tory supporter</a>.</p><p>After the X Factor winner''s single, the Children in Need tune and all the rest, I''m actually warming to the idea of Barlow as pop laureate. It makes sense for there to be an inspirational Barlow-ballad for every occasion, whether it''s a Eurovision song contest that needs winning, a royal couple requiring a first dance or a World Cup squad demanding an anthem. It''s just amazing that the 2012 Olympics have so far escaped a Barlow-penned allstar singalong. "Team GB" has a bit of a ring to it, don''t you think?</p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/culture&k=Gary+Barlow&k=The+X+Factor&k=Pop+and+rock" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/culture/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/culture/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=Gary+Barlow%3A+the+one-man+songwriting+factory+Article+1647833&ch=Culture&c2=60753&c4=Gary+Barlow%2CX+Factor+%28TV+and+radio%29%2CPop+and+rock+%28Music+genre%29&c3=The+Guardian&c6=Peter+Robinson&c7=11-Oct-16&c8=1647833&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: culture/2011/oct/16/gary-balow-songwriting|2011-10-16T21:13:35+01:00|3d8ec74d29e0e7f1c8fd3a6db38bffde784f1e63 -->', NULL, 'Culture', 'The Guardian', NULL, '2011-10-16 22:13:39'),
