(1108, 4, 'guard_bd160b00d8955ed022755498a7e11c55', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/public-leaders-network/blog/2011/oct/17/partners-public-sector-service', 'Take your partners for public services', 'Craig Dearden-Philips', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/10/14/1318586530243/ballroom-dancing-003.jpg', '2011-10-17 01:30:42', NULL, '<p>Joint ventures between spin-out providers and the third or private sectors could be the way forward, argues <strong>Craig Dearden-Philips</strong></p>', '<!-- Redistribution rights for this field are unavailable -->', NULL, 'Public Leaders Network', 'guardian.co.uk', NULL, '2011-10-17 04:11:04'),
(1109, 4, 'guard_cef9fd55067347d43f1c1209a64fffd0', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/public-leaders-network/blog/2011/oct/17/angry-britain-lead', 'Angry Britain: how to lead', 'Richard Wilson', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/10/13/1318521953786/riot-smashed-shop-003.jpg', '2011-10-17 01:36:42', NULL, '<p>The recession has brought much of Britain to boiling point. <strong>Richard Wilson</strong> outlines six steps to help public leaders deal with it</p>', '<p>Anger is in the air, on the streets, in the workplace, even in our homes. Upheaval in the economy is creating discontent at all levels. And for those of us leading the public sector we''re feeling it most acutely. If by some miracle you have some job security many of your friends and colleagues will have lost theirs.</p><p>Beyond job losses we''re all facing a barrage of discontent internally and externally. Internally, as we face the challenge of supporting colleagues adapt to new roles, pay deals and priorities, many of which they do not like or accept. Externally, unease is all too obvious from the August riots and their aftermath, to the subtler but no less passionate and visible campaigns to save services and stop the cuts.</p><p>What makes all of this especially difficult to stomach is that many of us never agreed to the changes that are fuelling the anger. And even if we did agree with some of them, we rarely supported its handling. So we''re left trying to hold together our organisations and communities when we would never have allowed this to happen in the first place.</p><p>Overly positivistic management gurus talk about clearing out "dead wood" or creating the space for essential "disruptive innovation". But we and our colleagues are human and humans find change hard. We just do. It creates anxiety and makes many of us angry. And with the double dip looming things are going to get angrier before they get calmer.</p><p>So what to do? In these angry times how do we make sure that our organisations, communities and lives don''t get derailed by a society at boiling point? Here are six steps that might just help you navigate the anger around you:</p><h2>1 Face the music</h2><p>It''s vital that leaders acknowledge the existence of any anger, conflict and uncertainty. We''ve all been in organisations when the boss has failed to do this through ignorance, incompetence or cowardice. Don''t be one of those. You don''t need to agree with whatever you''re acknowledging but if people feel that at least their concerns are acknowledged it is the vital starting point. This is relevant when working with the public as well. When communities raise concerns about service changes, recognise those concerns, regardless of whether you think their concerns are well founded. That is not the point.</p><h2>2 Communicate authentically</h2><p>When facing the angry music, explain it as you see it. Be as authentic as you can. Avoid management jargon at all costs – it will just serve to alienate you further. Don''t talk about "capacity overhead streamlining", talk about "friends and colleagues who have gone and will be badly missed".  Always acknowledge that your view is necessarily partial. Use subjective language to make this clear: ''In my opinion…" not "…this is a fact". If you can, explain the personal challenges you are facing, with a view to building common ground between them and you.</p><h2>3 Create clarity </h2><p>If a sense of injustice is often the spark for civic unrest, uncertainty is the fuel that maintains it. Outline very clear next steps even if those steps are creating a plan as opposed to having one. What people need is a concrete sense that whoever is in charge is in charge and knows what they are doing. Even if they don''t like what''s being proposed, a proposal is often better than no proposal. If a library''s being closed, for example, make it clear which library services are being maintained and how. What are your plans for the premises? What will you do with the books? Make all this as explicit as possible especially to the staff (first) and users (second).</p><h2>4 Establish shared goals</h2><p>Anxiety and anger can create doubt around people''s intentions. Wherever possible identify common goals. These could be high-level, such as improving the community and protecting the vulnerable, goals which people on all sides would agree with. Having established these, the next step is working out how to achieve them. Taking the library example: if there are areas for negotiation such as where library books will be located, whether to move some services online, or selecting which premises are to close, create space to discuss and agree these decisions with staff and community members. This could be through community workshops or online debates involving the public and press. This way not only can you channel public anger usefully, you can also harness the expertise you may otherwise miss.</p><h2>5 Empower others</h2><p>Anger is a powerful force that is at the heart of many effective organisations and projects. Do whatever you can to channel that anger into something meaningful. This may include giving other people the responsibility and support to solve the problems they now face. There''s nothing more frustrating than feeling a sense of injustice and not being able to do anything about it. Conversely, there are few things more empowering than a sense of injustice and the explicit mandate and support to do something about it.</p><p>Try giving colleagues or the community channels through which to "save" their services or jobs. In 2010 Lincolnshire council faced considerable public opposition to closing some of its museums and galleries. In response, the council gave the community the chance to put forward business plans to keep the facilities open. It was more of a platitude than a considered policy, but to the council''s surprise the community came back with some viable options that have led to many of the facilities being saved. The council is still providing some finance but a fraction of what it once did.</p><h2>6 Keep talking </h2><p>Angry and uncertain conditions make things change in unpredictable ways. This means you''ll want to keep talking to others to understand how their frustrations change and develop new plans with them in response. It will also be vital to ensure that uncertainty doesn''t raise its ugly face again. This is easy to say but challenging to do in the often hectic and reactive environments we now find ourselves. Try a mix of approaches – Facebook, Twitter and Youtube as well as more traditional community meetings. Different people like different ways of "talking". Be vigilant, assume you''re not communicating enough and continually check your assumptions with others.</p><p>Despite the malaise many of us feel that if handled well the tough times we now face may be fruitful. They are forcing many of us to reflect in ways we otherwise wouldn''t have. We all know tales of how the darkest nights have laid the foundations for the brightest days. And as we''ve seen, if handled properly anger can and often is a powerful force for good.</p><p>But that shouldn''t dissuade us from acknowledging that in those dark moments life is hard. That''s why we get mad  in the first place. So let''s not "keep calm and carry on", but get mad and motivated and try to make a difference to the mess we''re in.</p><p><em>Richard Wilson is director of Wilsonielsen, @richardwi1son</em></p><p><strong>This article is published by </strong><a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/guardian-professional" title=""><strong>Guardian Professional</strong></a><strong>. Join the Guardian </strong><a href="http://reg.guardian.managemyaccount.co.uk/public-leaders/start.php" title=""><strong>Public Leaders Network</strong></a><strong> free to receive regular emails on the issues at the top of the professional agenda</strong></p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/public-leaders-network&k=Public+Leaders+Network&k=HR&k=Frontline" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/public-leaders-network/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/public-leaders-network/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=Angry+Britain%3A+how+to+lead+Article+1647408&ch=Public+Leaders+Network&c2=60753&c4=PRO%3A+Public+Leaders+Network%2CPRO%3A+HR+%28Public+leaders+network%29%2CPRO%3A+Frontline+%28Public+leaders+network%29&c3=guardian.co.uk&c6=Richard+Wilson&c7=11-Oct-17&c8=1647408&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: public-leaders-network/blog/2011/oct/17/angry-britain-lead|2011-10-17T03:11:00+01:00|ec82607093f021721a021c116316b0bcce76dbd1 -->', NULL, 'Public Leaders Network', 'guardian.co.uk', NULL, '2011-10-17 04:11:04'),
(1111, 4, 'guard_d78e0b47377359fd6dd0425512b3794f', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2011/oct/17/st-louis-cardinals-brewers-live-six', 'St Louis Cardinals vs. Milwaukee Brewers - live!', 'David Lengel', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Sport/Pix/pictures/2011/10/16/1318799984150/Milwaukee-Brewers-Prince--003.jpg', '2011-10-17 02:33:00', NULL, '<p><strong>St Louis Cardinals vs. Milwaukee Brewers:</strong> live inning-by-inning coverage of NLCS game six</p>', '<!-- Block 11 --><p><span class="timestamp">Bottom 1st:</span> So after Jackson allows Hart to leave the building, the Cards hurler gets Nyjer Morgan, Ryan Braun and Prince fielder in order. A good inning after a little hiccup. Cardinals 4 Brewers 1</p><!-- Block 10 --><p><span class="timestamp">Bottom 1st:</span> Ice breaker-Corey Hart takes Edwin Jackson deep to centerfield to lead off the ballgame for the Brewers. The tense crowd has something to shout about, and a run on the board. <strong>Cardinals 4 Brewers 1</strong></p><!-- Block 9 --><p><span class="timestamp">Middle 1st:</span> Apologies for the technical difficulties. Like Milwaukee, we''re playing from behind here. Normal service is close to returning.</p><!-- Block 8 --><p><span class="timestamp">Top 1st:</span> God takes pity on Marcum, allowing the rocked brewer hurler to strike him out. Probably not the start fans in the great state of Wisconsin were looking for. Cardinals 4 Brewers 0</p><!-- Block 7 --><p>Albert Pujols is out at the plate after Marcum picks up Matt Holliday''s dribbler and throws to the catcher Lucroy who applies the tag...too late. Never mind, he''s called out anyway. Cardinals fans can''t be too upset though, not after David Freese (yes, a cool customer that Freese) launches a three run home run over Ryan Braun''s head in left field. Marcum has spit the bit in a big spot. <strong>Cardinals 4 Brewers 0</strong></p><!-- Block 6 --><p><span class="timestamp">Top 1st:</span> Marcum is going for Pujols, even with first base open, so Brewers manager Ron Roenicke isn''t doing the Barry Bonds thing here in the first. Still, Pujols draws a walk, so now it''s two on, one out for Lance Berkman, who is just another Cardinals reclamation project paying dividends. Berkman delivers, scoring Furcal after a base hit that turns into a double after clumsy defense by Milwaukee. <strong>Cardinals 1 Brewers 0</strong></p><!-- Block 5 --><p><span class="timestamp">Top 1st:</span> Marcum is going for Pujols, even with first base open, so Brewers manager Ron Roenickie isn''t doing the Barry Bonds thing here in the first. Still, Pujols draws a walk, so now it''s two on, one out for Lance Berkman, who is just another Cardinals reclamation project paying dividends.</p><!-- Block 4 --><p><span class="timestamp">Top 1st:</span> Here''s Shaun Marcum, who got hammered in his last outing, whcih was Game Two, allowing five runs and seven hits in four innings. Rafael Furcal is up first, and pops up to Yuniesky Betancourt, who makes a great play with his back to the infield, on the run, to get the Cards lead off man. Marcum isn''t as fortunate with John Jay, who singles to left field. That means Pujols is up with one out and a man on. Marcum puts one in the dirt while Jay is off and running-he slides safely into second, and we got a situation here in Milwaukee early.</p><!-- Block 3 --><p>Ladies and gentlemen, boys and girls. Please rise for the playing of our national anthem...or not.</p><!-- Block 2 --><p><span class="timestamp">warmups:</span> In the interest of consistency, now that I''ve arrived at our Brooklyn basement HQ, God has been inserted in the St. Louis lineup, batting 7th for the Cardinals. </p><p>While on the subject of the supernatural, why do I get the idea that if La Russa gets struck down he will become more powerful than we could possibly imagine...something to chew on as we enter Game Six, a decisive game, that is, if you''re a Brewers fan. Do or die for the Brew Crew inside Miller Park, which by the way, has its roof closed tonight.</p><!-- Block 1 --><p><span class="timestamp">Preamble:</span> The question now is: Who will play the Texas Rangers in the 2011 World Series?</p><p>The Lone Star state team earned the approval of Nolan Ryan and George W Bush with <a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2011/oct/16/detroit-tigers-texas-rangers-live-six">a 15-5 destruction of the Detroit Tigers in ALCS Game Six</a>, courtesy of a <a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2011/oct/16/detroit-tigers-texas-rangers-live-six#block-12">nine-run 3rd inning</a> and <a href="http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2011/oct/16/detroit-tigers-texas-rangers-live-six#block-33">a record sixth home run of the series from Nelson Cruz</a>.</p><p>The St Louis Cardinals are just one win away from joining them and giving Albert Pujols the perfect stage for his Redbirds farewell - if this is to be his last season with his only career club.</p><p>Milwaukee must win two games at home - tonight and Monday - to reach the Fall Classic and need the big guns of Prince Fielder and Ryan Braun to fire.</p><p>Lineups:</p><p>ST. LOUIS CARDINALS<br />1. Rafael Furcal, SS<br />2. Jon Jay, CF<br />3. Albert Pujols, 1B<br />4. Lance Berkman, RF<br />5. Matt Holliday, LF<br />6. David Freese, 3B<br />7. God, C<br />8. Nick Punto, 2B<br />9. Edwin Jackson, RHP</p><p>MILWAUKEE BREWERS<br />1. Corey Hart, RF<br />2. Nyjer Morgan, CF<br />3. Ryan Braun, LF<br />4. Prince Fielder, 1B<br />5. Rickie Weeks, 2B<br />6. Jerry Hairston Jr., 3B<br />7. Yuniesky Betancourt, SS<br />8. Jonathan Lucroy, C<br />9. Shaun Marcum, RHP</p><p>First pitch is at 8pm ET.</p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/sport&k=MLB&k=US+sport&k=Sport" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/sport/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/sport/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=St+Louis+Cardinals+vs.+Milwaukee+Brewers+-+live%21+Article+1648485&ch=Sport&c2=60753&c4=MLB%2CUS+sports%2CSport&c3=guardian.co.uk&c6=David+Lengel&c7=11-Oct-17&c8=1648485&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: sport/2011/oct/17/st-louis-cardinals-brewers-live-six|2011-10-17T03:11:00+01:00|0f2de54a5b1825b92cfa891bb503200ecbfec577 -->', NULL, 'Sport', 'guardian.co.uk', NULL, '2011-10-17 04:11:04'),
(1112, 4, 'guard_5ec5c2e51dab94c332c296a8946a9104', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/football/2011/oct/17/wayne-rooney-england', 'Wayne Rooney receives support from the Montenegro defender he kicked', NULL, 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Sport/Pix/columnists/2011/10/17/1318811212336/Wayne-Rooney-of-England-003.jpg', '2011-10-17 02:42:00', NULL, 'Wayne Rooney apologised to the Montenegro defender Miodrag Dzudovic after kicking him during England''s 2012 qualifier', '<!-- Redistribution rights for this field are unavailable -->', NULL, 'Football', 'guardian.co.uk', NULL, '2011-10-17 04:11:04'),
(1113, 4, 'guard_b89d35d528f8c060b6c4d3a8fb8eb47b', 'http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2011/oct/17/gary-hoffman-northern-rock-bid', 'Gary Hoffman set to make Northern Rock bid', 'Jill Treanor', 'http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2011/10/17/1318812343408/Gary-Hoffman-the-former-b-003.jpg', '2011-10-17 02:47:40', NULL, 'Early release from ''no bid'' agreement enables former boss to buy nationalised lender', '<p>Gary Hoffman, the former boss of Northern Rock, is preparing to lead a bid for the nationalised lender after being released two weeks early from a "no bid" agreement.</p><p>Hoffman was barred for a year from bidding for Northern Rock when he suddenly quit last November to head NBNK, a vehicle set up to bid for banks.</p><p>That moratorium on making a bid was not due to expire until the first week of November. But Northern Rock and UK Financial Investments, which controls the taxpayer stakes in the bailed out banks, last week agreed to release Hoffman from the restriction.</p><p>The move is significant, according to City sources, as it will allow NBNK to potentially unite Northern Rock with the 632 Lloyds Banking Group branches it is already trying to buy.</p><p>The Independent Commission on Banking wants any successful bidder for the Lloyds branches to be able to link up with another branch network to increase its market share beyond the 4.5% share of the Lloyds branches.</p><p>NBNK had originally wanted to do this with the UK branches of National Australia Bank – Clydesdale and Yorkshire – but failed to do so. NAB also had been expected to bid for the Lloyds branches but is still sitting on the sidelines.</p><p>The government is hoping it can find a buyer for Northern Rock, which has been carved into a good and bad bank, even though it has little hope of selling off the stakes in Lloyds and Royal Bank of Scotland.</p><p>The "good" part of Northern Rock has been stripped of the original taxpayer loan but received a £1.4bn cash injection last year to enable it to resume lending. That £1.4bn has been regarded as the price at which the government needs to sell Northern Rock although officials are braced for criticism if forced to sell at a loss.</p><p>Virgin Money and venture capitalists JC Flowers are thought to be the other bidders for Northern Rock, which would not comment last night. Neither would NBNK or UKFI.</p><div class="gu_advert">\n        <iframe marginheight="0" frameborder="0" width="300px" height="250px" style="border: none" src="http://resource.guim.co.uk/global/adcode/generatehtml?slot=Bottom&partner=guardianapis.com/business&k=Northern+Rock&k=Banking&k=Business&k=UK+news" marginwidth="0" scrolling="NO">\n          <a href="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/click_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/business/oas.html/@Bottom" rel="nofollow">\n              <img src="http://oas.guardian.co.uk/RealMedia/ads/adstream_nx.ads/guardianapis.com/business/oas.html/@Bottom" alt="Ads by The Guardian"></img>\n          </a>\n        </iframe>\n      </div><img src=''http://hits.guardian.co.uk/b/ss/guardiangu-api/1/H.20.3/98867?ns=guardian&pageName=Gary+Hoffman+set+to+make+Northern+Rock+bid+Article+1648493&ch=Business&c2=60753&c4=Northern+Rock+%28Business%29%2CBanking+%28Business+sector%29%2CBusiness%2CUK+news&c3=The+Guardian&c6=Jill+Treanor&c7=11-Oct-17&c8=1648493&c9=Article'' width=''1'' height=''1'' /><!-- Guardian Watermark: business/2011/oct/17/gary-hoffman-northern-rock-bid|2011-10-17T03:11:02+01:00|ffdff71494d42f26e9f9c849cf8c4ef8a8df303d -->', NULL, 'Business', 'The Guardian', NULL, '2011-10-17 04:11:05'),
